<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A TV Finale for a Video Presidency  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A familiar-looking man strode purposefully along
a backstage corridor, alone -- except, of course, for the camera
that tracked him.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's smiling, loaded-for-bear visage was splashed
across the huge video screen at the Democratic National Convention
in Los Angeles -- and broadcast to homes across the nation -- as
cheering rose at the Staples Center arena.
</P>
<P>
   Lasting more than a minute before he emerged at the podium,
Clinton's long, long walk served as quite a buildup. It was a
galvanizing TV interlude. And very much his style.
</P>
<P>
   The speech he then delivered, which was carried in its entirety
by the big three broadcast networks, the all-news cable networks,
plus PBS and C-SPAN, had been described as Clinton's valedictory
address.
</P>
<P>
   As a passing of the torch to his vice president, Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Even as possibly stealing the thunder from Gore, the party's
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's star turn Monday night was something else: a big
TV finish for a video presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Beforehand, CBS anchor Dan Rather called his farewell ''a slo-mo
Hollywood fade-out.''
</P>
<P>
   On MSNBC, commentator Chris Matthews said ''Clinton's job
tonight is to leave. Nicely, effectively, but to leave,'' while on
Fox News Channel, Bill Kristol argued, ''I'm not sure that can
happen. This is Bill Clinton's convention.''
</P>
<P>
   But CNN's Jeff Greenfield had no doubt that, before his retreat,
Clinton would deliver the goods at the podium. ''If you know
someone who's spent eight years waiting for Bill Clinton to
self-destruct, send them a bottle of Maalox. They'll need it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has defied his opponents' expectations many times in the
past, and often television was involved.
</P>
<P>
   He won his first term in 1992 in part by his masterful use of
TV, whether it was sparring with talk-show host Phil Donahue or
playing the saxophone on ''Arsenio Hall'' or rescuing his candidacy
with an interview on ''60 Minutes'' with wife Hillary Rodham
Clinton at his side.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will be remembered for many things. But his nearly eight
years in the White House were marked by a succession of vivid TV
moments. (Don't forget his MTV-aired disclosure on the
boxers-or-briefs issue.)
</P>
<P>
   Some, of course, were moments he would rather have avoided, yet
he nearly always made the most of them.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the summer's hottest telecast was his
presidential mea culpa, four minutes of it, during which he
cautioned that any marital dalliance was a matter ''between me, the
two people I love most -- my wife and our daughter -- and our God.''
He drew an estimated 68 million viewers and, by most assessments,
satisfied his audience.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last week, Clinton was on TV screens with another
message of contrition: ''Surely no fair-minded person would blame
him (Gore) for any mistake that I made.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the convention, he was shrewdly pre-emptive. ''Whatever
you think about me ...,'' he said as he built to his speech's grand
conclusion. After Monday night, this TV president left no doubt:
The success of the prospective Al Gore Show could depend on
Clinton's persuasiveness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
