<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Army Frees Another Hostage  </HEADLINE>
By WILL WEISSERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- In a pre-dawn strike Monday, Colombian
soldiers rescued another kidnapping victim held by leftist rebels
south of the capital Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   The troops were chasing kidnappers who escaped Sunday with two
hostages after a raid that freed five people, including a prominent
Colombian journalist-businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers tracked the retreating rebels from the Revolutionary
Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, during the night and rescued
Colombian Edgar Andres Vargas early Monday, army Gen. Jorge Mora
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had excellent intelligence information before we mounted
any rescues,'' Mora said. ''That intelligence made the second
rescue effort easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The search for those holding the remaining hostage was
continuing, Mora said.
</P>
<P>
   Guillermo Cortes, 73, former owner of a Bogota soccer team and
part owner of a popular TV news show as well as several magazines,
was kidnapped from his weekend home outside Bogota on Jan. 22 by
FARC guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels had demanded $1 million for his release. According to
the government, FARC is responsible for about 30 percent of the
8,000 annual kidnappings in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-kidnapping squad rescued the five hostages Sunday from
a guerrilla camp in the mountains between the towns of Medina and
Los Alpes, about 55 miles south of Bogota, Mora said.
</P>
<P>
   ''A group of soldiers successfully surrounded those guarding the
victims without them realizing it,'' Mora said of the Sunday
mission. One kidnapper was killed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth hostage was rescued Monday near the same area, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those released Sunday was German Rolf Sommerfeld, 57, an
engineer who has lived in Colombia for 12 years. He was kidnapped
last August when he was pulled from his car by masked FARC
guerrillas on a crowded Bogota street.
</P>
<P>
   Also rescued were Colombians Alejandro Londono and Ricardo
Ramirez and an Austrian-Colombian dual citizen, Jaime Correal.
</P>
<P>
   The isolated rugged region is so dominated by the FARC that any
army movements in the area are usually reported to rebels by local
residents, giving the rebels time to move hostages between several
makeshift camps, Mora said.
</P>
<P>
   Sommerfeld gave his rescuers high marks.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was all very professional,'' Sommerfeld said on Bogota's
Caracol Radio. ''We were in bed waiting for (the rebels) to bring
us breakfast, but it never came. The solders arrived instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebel activity has escalated apparently in the run-up to
President Clinton's planned visit to Colombia on Aug. 30. A car
bomb exploded outside a police station in Bogota on Sunday,
injuring a civilian. And on Monday, police said they had defused
explosives from a sedan in an upscale north Bogota neighborhood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 0042 </TRAILER>
