<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Koreans Visit Families in South  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Smiling and waving, a group of 100
separated family members from North Korea arrived in South Korea on
Tuesday for temporary reunions with relatives they have not seen
for half a century.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian-made passenger jet of Air Koryo, North Korea's
national airline, ferried the aging family members from Pyongyang
on a 50-minute flight to Seoul's Kimpo airport. It then picked up
100 South Koreans and took off for similar exchanges in the North.
</P>
<P>
   Spectators clapped as the North Koreans, mostly men in dark
suits wearing pins with the image of their revered late leader, Kim
Il Sung, walked through airport customs and boarded buses bound for
a Seoul hotel. The visitors included an 84-year-old woman in a
traditional Korean gown with a cane who came to meet her elder
sister and a niece.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am very happy,'' said the woman, Hwang Ui Bun, who grinned
with delight.
</P>
<P>
   Family reunions are one of the most emotional issues that have
defined the longrunning standoff between the two Koreas, which were
once devoted to each other's downfall but have made great strides
toward reconciliation in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the North Korean delegation, 78-year-old Yoo Mi
Young, told reporters that she was very happy and that the reunions
this week were not an isolated event and more would follow.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's only the beginning,'' said Yoo, who defected to North
Korea from the South in 1986 along with her husband, former South
Korean Foreign Minister Choi Duk Shin. He died in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The 100 North Korean family members were accompanied by 31
officials and 20 journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Rapprochement between the communist North and the democratic
South accelerated after their leaders held a summit in June and
pledged to work toward eventual reunification.
</P>
<P>
   That goal remains distant and complex, but events like the
family reunions -- the first since 1985 -- are likely to help
dissipate some of the animosity that has flourished since the
1950-53 Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   While this week's reunions constitute a political gesture of
good will between governments, they are a source of private joy,
discovery and pain for those involved.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Jung-ho, a 91-year-old South Korean, said he expected to
meet a 60-year-old son when he arrives in Pyongyang, the North
Korean capital.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, who bought watches and gold rings as gifts for his
relatives in the North, last saw his son when he fled alone to
South Korea in 1951 during the chaos of war.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first thing I want to ask him is: What happened to the
other family members? Then I would ask how he endured through all
those difficult years,'' Kim said before heading to the airport for
the flight to Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day reunions began on Aug. 15, a national holiday in
both Koreas that is the anniversary of the peninsula's liberation
from Japanese colonial rule at the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech broadcast live on national television, South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung vowed to work to end the threat of war
between the Koreas and pursue economic and other exchanges ahead of
reunification.
</P>
<P>
   ''Attempts at unification by force of arms and unification by
absorption taking advantage of economic superiority will only lead
to war and destruction,'' Kim told an audience of independence
fighters, political leaders and diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea, which has one of the largest economies in the
world, is far wealthier than North Korea, where poor centralized
planning, heavy military spending and bad weather have undercut the
economy and forced Pyongyang to appeal for outside food aid.
</P>
<P>
   The family members who arrived from Pyongyang were scheduled to
meet their South Korean relatives at a Seoul conference center
Tuesday afternoon. Their schedule includes private meetings in
hotel rooms, banquets and city tours.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean visitors to the North had a similar schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Yo in-yul, an 81-year-old South Korean, fled North Korea in 1951
with his parents, leaving behind a 9-year-old sister.
</P>
<P>
   Yo expected to see his sister, Yo Jung-suk, on arrival in
Pyongyang Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''My heart is aching whenever I recall the moment of separation.
She held me by the hand and cried, begging me to take her along,''
Yo said.
</P>
<P>
   Family reunions are a pressing issue because many aging family
members have only a few years left to see relatives. Many people
have died without making contact with relatives. There is no mail,
telephone or other direct means of communication between private
citizens in the two Koreas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rapprochement, uneasiness lingers in the South over
apparent political use of the event by the North.
</P>
<P>
   While South Korea chose its 100 finalists for the reunions
through a computer lottery, the North Korean list includes a
renowned poet, a painter, a film maker, a scientist and other
celebrated people. And all the Northern visitors are natives of
South Korea who defected to the North.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean critics said loyalty to the communist system
appeared to be the most important criterion for getting on the
North's list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 0054 </TRAILER>
