<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Addresses Democratic Party  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In an emotional last hurrah to the party
faithful, Bill Clinton thanked the nation for giving him ''the
chance to live my dreams.'' In return, the first two-term
Democratic president in a half century said he tried to better
Americans' lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now, with hair grayer and wrinkles deeper, but with the same
optimism and hope I brought to the work I so love eight years ago,
I want you to know my heart is filled with gratitude,'' he said in
his political finale to the Democratic National Convention on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The hall was filled to the rafters with Democrats who cheered
wildly before and after Clinton's 41-minute speech. They shouted
''Thank you! Thank you!'' and waved placards that read ''America,
better than ever!''
</P>
<P>
   Mixing nostalgia with partisan applause lines, Clinton said he
had delivered on the promise of 1992, saying, ''I ran for president
to change the future,'' for those left behind in America.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ended his speech with the words ''I love you.'' With a
wave, the president left the stage with his wife Hillary Rodham
Clinton and daughter Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton asked voters to help elect his understudy Al Gore as his
successor, to send his wife to the Senate and -- for the sake of his
own legacy -- to refute the charge of Republican presidential
candidate George W. Bush that America, blessed with prosperity, had
coasted during the Clinton years. He didn't mention Bush by name.
</P>
<P>
   America gave him the chance to turn his ideals into action,
Clinton said, ''after I made one of the very best decisions of my
life: asking Al Gore to be my partner.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeated several refrains about how much better off
Americans are at the end of the Clinton-Gore administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are more hopeful,'' he said four times, because of tax
cuts, education reforms, new job creation and welfare reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are more secure,'' he said three times, because of less
crime, better health care and a cleaner environment.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are more free,'' he said twice, because of less bigotry and
less discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   In closing, he said: ''My fellow Americans, the future of our
country is in your hands. You must think hard, feel deeply, and
choose wisely.
</P>
<P>
   ''Remember, keep putting people first. Keep building those
bridges. And don't stop thinking about tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans responded even before Clinton had left the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ''This speech was about Bill Clinton trying to write his own
legacy, not about Al Gore's future,'' said Bush spokesman Ari
Fleischer. ''Instead of passing the baton to Al Gore, Bill Clinton
used it to beat his own drum. The vice president remains in Bill
Clinton's shadow.''
</P>
<P>
   Who leads America next, Clinton said, is the American people's
and not his. But he said all he could to influence it.
</P>
<P>
   ''Al Gore and Joe Lieberman will keep our prosperity going by
paying down the debt, investing in education and health care, and
in family tax cuts that we can afford,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In stark contrast, the GOP wants to spend every dime of our
projected surplus and then some -- leaving nothing to extend the
life of Medicare and Social Security, nothing for emergencies,
nothing in case the projected surpluses don't come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was only the third president in modern history to make
his farewells to a party after having served two full terms. The
others were both Republicans -- Dwight D. Eisenhower, who succeeded
Truman in 1953, and Ronald Reagan, who ousted Democrat Jimmy Carter
and took office in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton attended his first convention in 1972, not a good year
for Democrats. He spoke at the 1988 gathering, in a speech so
ponderously long that he still gets ribbed about it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech was the main event of the convention's opening
night. On Tuesday, he will meet up with Gore on the campaign trail
in Michigan for a symbolic passing of the party torch.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who watched the speech from Missouri, praised Clinton's
speech as a ''very strong case'' for the record of the Clinton-Gore
years and looked ahead to the hand-off in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a symbolic message that's more important than most of the
words we'll be using,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The end-of-an-era theme was underscored by a tribute video
similar to the ''Man From Hope'' biography that introduced Clinton
to millions of voters at the 1992 convention.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton was aware of the risk of over-playing his
moment before the delegates. He knows ''it's his moment to get off
the stage and let someone else get on the stage and do the job,''
White House chief of staff John Podesta said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking his leave, Clinton also hoped to energize Democrats with
some partisan fire.
</P>
<P>
   But he hoped that his farewell address, like President Reagan's
in 1988, would be remembered for its softer, more evocative
moments.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, a student of American history, is mindful of the
historical shift in political conventions -- away from the drama of
nomination fights and toward the gauzy world of first impressions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 0057 </TRAILER>
