<DOCNO> APW20000815.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Honor Ex-President Carter  </HEADLINE>
By EUN-KYUNG KIM
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Jimmy Carter hadn't planned to attend the
Democratic National Convention, even though his presidential status
made him an automatic delegate and Al Gore pressed him to make a
speech.
</P>
<P>
   But then the vice president came back with a more appealing
offer -- a video tribute Monday night to the only surviving former
Democratic president.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't have to worry about details of a speech,'' he said in
an interview with The Associated Press. ''Now I can enjoy the
convention with my children and grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter mingled among the Georgia delegates on the convention
floor ''with my friends'' before he and his wife, Rosalynn, slipped
unannounced into a VIP section prior to his tribute.
</P>
<P>
   California Sen. Dianne Feinstein introduced Carter to the crowd,
who reciprocated with a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-minute video showcased Carter's accomplishments as
president and peacemaker. The audience cheered throughout several
spots, particularly during the footage of the signing ceremony for
the Camp David peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to be associated with my name, maybe the words
peace and human rights. That would be my preference,'' Carter said
at the conclusion of the video.
</P>
<P>
   During the tribute, Carter smiled broadly and his wife appeared
to be blinking back tears.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton later paid tribute to Carter during his
convention address, saying that ''in the great tradition of
President Jimmy Carter ... we are still the world's leading force
for human rights around the world. Thank you, President Carter.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he ''really appreciated'' the acknowledgment.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was heartwarming to me,'' he said on CNN's Larry King Live.
</P>
<P>
   Following the tribute, Carter received a call from Gore, who
''just thanked me for being here and congratulated me.'' Carter
called the vice president ''a very close personal friend of mine
for 25 years,'' explaining that Gore was elected to Congress the
same year he was elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Carter lost his re-election bid to Ronald Reagan in 1980. His
term was marred by an energy shortage, skyrocketing inflation, and
the Iran hostage crisis but also included several highlights,
including the successful 1978 Camp David summit when he helped
hammer out a Middle East peace deal between Egyptian President
Anwar Sadat and Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin.
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the White House, Carter's popularity has increased
along with his reputation as a globe-trotting diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   Some delegates criticized the Democratic Party for failing to
recognize Carter during previous conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's long overdue to pay tribute to President Carter,'' said
Rep. John Lewis of Georgia, Carter's home state.
</P>
<P>
   Carter was ''treated like a pariah at earlier conventions,''
said fellow Georgia delegate, former Rep. Buddy Darden.
</P>
<P>
   But Carter disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never have felt excluded and I never have been treated
poorly,'' he said. ''I've always felt that I've been treated quite
well'' by the party.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the two conventions where he was nominated as president,
Carter made several other prime-time convention speeches. He said
he decided against going to the 1996 gathering because President
Clinton and Gore were being renominated.
</P>
<P>
   ''They didn't need my help,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 0058 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000815.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Braces for Rebel Attacks  </HEADLINE>
By NEELESH MISRA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India (AP) -- Security forces turned Srinagar into a
garrison town Monday, the eve of India's independence day, as they
sought to prevent further rebel attacks like the car bombing that
killed 14 people last week.
</P>
<P>
   No violence was immediately reported in Srinagar, but an
explosion ripped through a passenger train in northern India on
Monday night, killing nine people and wounding 33 others, Press
Trust of India news agency reported Tuesday. No one claimed
responsibility for the train blast in Roza Gaon, nearly 300 miles
southeast of New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of soldiers, paramilitary troops and police spread
across Srinagar, summer capital of disputed Kashmir, and other
areas vulnerable to attack by Islamic guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in a war zone. We are taking all precautions,'' said
Kul Bhushan Jandial, the state government's chief spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir is the focus of an Islamic insurgency that has killed at
least 25,000 people in the past 11 years. More than a dozen
militant groups have been fighting Indian forces, demanding
independence or Kashmir's merger with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, suspected militants attacked paramilitary patrols
and wounded three soldiers and five civilians in Kashmir. The
attacks came a day after two land mines killed six soldiers, 10
rebels died in gun battles with government troops and three
explosions injured 42 other people.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two powerful blasts Monday injured eight people,
including four policemen, in Kanpur, 240 miles southeast of New
Delhi, in the state of Uttar Pradesh, also in northern India, the
Press Trust of India news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   There was no word on who carried out the attack. Kashmir
separatist have threatened violence during independence
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpshooters took positions Monday overlooking Bakshi Stadium
in Srinagar, where Chief Minister Farooq Abdullah, Kashmir's top
elected leader, was to give a speech Tuesday. Police fear rocket
attacks on the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers wearing bulletproof vests and helmets inspected cars at
checkpoints and looked for bombs under cars in parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cars have been stolen. Some of them could be used by the
militants in such attacks,'' Chavang Phunsog, Kashmir's principal
home secretary, told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Girish Chandra Saxena, the federal representative in
Kashmir, acknowledged human rights excesses by security forces in
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   ''This problem is inherent in the prevailing circumstances,
which have been created by the terrorist and their foreign
mentors,'' Saxenna said in a statement. He urged security forces to
''take care to minimize civilian casualties or losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Separatist guerrillas in the Kashmir Valley have observed
India's Independence Day as a ''Black Day'' since 1989. India
accuses neighboring Pakistan of fomenting and backing the
militancy, a charge Pakistan denies.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan President Rafiq Tarar said in an address Monday -- the
day his country celebrates independence from Britain -- that
Islamabad would continue to support the struggle in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, hopes for peace rose when Hezb-ul Mujahedeeen, the
main militant group, announced a cease-fire and the Indian
government responded by suspending its offensives.
</P>
<P>
   But peace talks fell through when India refused a demand to
include Pakistan in the discussions. The Hezb-ul Mujahedeen broke
the cease-fire with a car bomb in downtown Srinagar that killed 13
soldiers and a journalist and wounded 25 other people Aug. 8.
</P>
<P>
   India holds two-thirds of Kashmir and Pakistan the rest. The
hostile nuclear armed neighbors have fought two wars for control of
Kashmir since they won independence from Britain in 1947.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 0059 </TRAILER>
