<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, Aug. 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clintons Rally Democrats for 2000
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- President Clinton offered a triumphant review of his
years in office Monday night before the Democratic National Convention and
appealed to Americans to elect Al Gore as his successor. Clinton described his
vice president as a ''profoundly good man'' who will ''keep this progress and
prosperity going.'' The evening session ended to a rendition of ''Seventy-six
trombones,'' an upbeat counterpoint to the scene in the street outside the hall,
where police in riot gear struggled with protestors.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
First Lady Speaks at Convention
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Completing her transformation from first lady to U.S.
Senate candidate from New York, Hillary Rodham Clinton thanked Americans on
Monday night ''for your faith and support in good times -- and in bad.'' She
made a prime-time address to the Democratic National Convention just before
President Clinton offered his political farewell to the party faithful. Mrs.
Clinton hailed his administration and called for voters to elect Al Gore and Joe
Lieberman to carry on that work.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Protesters Clash With L.A. Police
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A festive protest concert outside the Democratic National
Convention turned violent Monday night as demonstrators began throwing chunks of
concrete and firing steel balls from slingshots at police who responded with
pepper-spray balls, rubber bullets and finally a charge on horseback. Police
herded the demonstrators to the far end of a designated protest area, pushing
them away from the convention hall. The confrontation originally involved about
300 people out of the crowd of 8,000 but then spread. Nine people were arrested
in an earlier clash.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hurricane Warnings Posted in Texas
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- As big storm approached from the Gulf of Mexico,
hurricane warnings went up Monday along 230 miles of coastline in Texas and
Mexico. By 11 p.m. EDT, Beryl had sustained winds of 50 mph. It was centered
about 115 miles south of Brownsville. Beryl could reach hurricane strength of at
least 75 mph before coming ashore Tuesday near the U.S.-Mexico border, said the
National Hurricane Center in Miami.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russians Trying To Rescue Sub
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The Russian navy is trying to find a way to rescue more than
100 sailors trapped at the bottom of the Barents Sea in a crippled submarine. By
early Tuesday, about a dozen military ships including a nuclear-powered cruiser
were at the site, Russian reports said. The chance of a happy ending was ''not
very high,'' the navy chief conceded. The Kursk, one of Russia's biggest nuclear
submarines, was apparently involved in a collision before it plunged hundreds of
feet near the Arctic Circle.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N. Koreans Visit Families in South
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A group of 100 separated family members from North
Korea arrived in South Korea Tuesday for temporary reunions with relatives they
have not seen for half a century. A passenger jet of Air Koryo, North Korea's
national airline, ferried the aging family members from Pyongyang on a 50-minute
flight to Seoul's Kimpo airport and prepared to pick up 100 South Koreans for
similar exchanges in the North.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Safety Experts: Widen Tire Recall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Safety advocates and attorneys suing Ford Motor Co. and
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. accused the companies Monday of dangerously limiting
the size of a Firestone tire recall, and urged them to broaden it. Company
officials said their actions were sufficient and that the overwhelmingly
majority of complaints were from the tires being recalled.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Social Security Turns 65
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WOODLAWN, Md. (AP) -- Social Security, the agency that provides a financial
safety net for millions of elderly and retired Americans, has reached the
milestone that most of its members await: its 65th birthday. About 300 past and
present Social Security Administration employees joined Commissioner Kenneth S.
Apfel Monday to dedicate a garden at the agency's Woodlawn headquarters. The
centerpiece is a bust of President Franklin Delano Roosevelt, who signed the
Social Security Act on Aug. 14, 1935.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Edge Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo stock market's main index inched higher Tuesday in
thin trading. The Nikkei gained 1.31 points to 16,155.22 in the morning session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Titans 30, Rams 3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Steve McNair threw for a touchdown, backup Neil
O'Donnell tossed two more and the defense got five sacks as the Tennessee Titans
routed the St. Louis Rams 30-3 Monday night in a preseason rematch of the Super
Bowl. The Titans played keepaway the entire first quarter, allowing St. Louis
just one series where the Rams went three-and-out. Eddie George had a night's
worth of work as he carried 15 times for 69 yards in two series that lasted 12
and 13 plays each.
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS 
</P>
