<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clintons Rally Democrats for 2000  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- President Clinton offered a triumphant review
of his years in office Monday night, exhorting the Democratic
National Convention to propel Al Gore on the road to succeed him.
Clinton described his vice president as a ''profoundly good man''
who will ''keep this progress and prosperity going.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My fellow Americans, are we better off today than we were
eight years ago? You bet we are,'' said the man who twice led his
party to victory.
</P>
<P>
   The evening session ended to a rendition of ''Seventy-six
trombones,'' an upbeat counterpoint to the scene outside the hall,
where police in riot gear and on horseback clashed with
demonstrators following an evening of music and protest.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' four-day political production was designed not
only to promote Gore and running mate Joseph Lieberman, but also to
stir memories of John F. Kennedy's nomination in this city 40 years
ago. Kennedy's image appeared on the video screen behind the
speaker's podium as the convention opened; his voice echoed in the
hall. His daughter, Caroline, addresses the delegates Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates cheered Clinton even before he stepped to the podium,
watching a giant video screen that captured him image he strolled
through an underground corridor. The noise drew louder when he made
it to the stage and delegates chanted, ''Thank you'' over and over
again.
</P>
<P>
   In his valedictory convention address as president, Clinton
praised Gore for his work in the White House. ''Whether it was
reforming welfare, protecting the environment, closing the digital
divide or bringing jobs to rural and urban America,'' said Clinton,
''there has been no stronger champion than Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the convention that twice nominated him for the
presidency, Clinton said Gore was ''always there'' when the tough
decisions were being made in the White House and that he would
succeed ''by paying down the debt, investing in education and
health care and in family tax cuts we can afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans responded even before Clinton had left the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ''This speech was about Bill Clinton trying to write his own
legacy, not about Al Gore's future,'' said spokesman Ari Fleischer.
''Instead of passing the baton to Al Gore, Bill Clinton used it to
beat his own drum. The vice president remains in Bill Clinton's
shadow.''
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton preceded her husband to the
podium, cheered loudly herself to the booming strains of ''New
York,'' her new home and site of her Senate candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaigned in Missouri as the convention's opening gavel
fell, stressing his commitment to Social Security and Medicare and
vowing an issue-oriented campaign setting out the choice between
parties. From the road he spoke to Clinton and thanked him for his
''generous and kind words.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The people on the other ticket are good men, I'll never attack
them personally,'' Gore said, referring to George W. Bush and Dick
Cheney. He said, ''The American people need to know the specifics
of how the American people would be affected if the other side
won.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton later completed the thought, telling 4,338 delegates and
many thousands more in the Staples Center arena, ''The GOP wants to
spend every dime of our projected surplus and then some -- leaving
nothing to extend the life of Medicare and Social Security, nothing
for emergencies, nothing in case the projected surpluses don't come
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from the convention hall, Democratic Sen. Joseph Biden of
Delaware candidly discussed the issue of Clinton's personal
failings and their impact on the party. ''We have been so cowered
as a party by a guy I love, Bill Clinton's incredible
indiscretions,'' he told Iowa's delegates. ''I think we should make
this election about integrity, I think we should make this election
about honesty. Not shy away from it,'' he said.	   The Democratic hope for their
convention week was for Gore to
emerge from Clinton's presidential shadow, gain a measure of credit
and respect for the accomplishments of the last eight years, but
avoid being tarred with the brush of Clinton's personal misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously the escapades of President Clinton in the White
House are still in people's memories but I think that time is
passing by,'' former President Carter said in an NBC interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has never been a hint of scandal about Al Gore,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hall, hundreds of protesters clashed with police
after a concert by the edgy rock band ''Rage Against the Machine.''
Activists threw chunks of dirt in the direction of police, who
responded by firing balls of pepper spray from paintball guns.
Protesters also sprayed police with ammonia and were firing steel
balls from slingshots, said California Highway Patrol Assistant
Chief Stan Perez. ''We're deploying en masse,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd inside the hall was unaware as they listened to
Clinton skewer the Republicans and urge four more years for the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''America's success was not a matter of chance; it was a matter
of choice,'' he said, rebutting claims by Georger W. Bush to the
contrary.
</P>
<P>
   He ridiculed Republicans for their dire predictions about his
first-term economic plan, a blueprint that he said has led to
soaring surpluses instead of deficits. ''The Republican said they
would not be held responsible for our economic policies,'' he said.
I hope the American people will take them at their word.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton repeated several refrains about how much better off
Americans are compared to the end of the Bush administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are more hopeful,'' he said three times, because of tax
cuts, new job creation and welfare reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are more secure,'' he said three times, because of less
crime, better health care and a cleaner environment.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are more free,'' he said twice, because of less bigotry and
less discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   He concluded his remarks with an appeal to voters, saying ''the
future of our country is in your hands. You must think hard, feel
deeply, and choose wisely.''
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Clinton struck many of the same themes.
Thinking back to the 1992 campaign, she said, ''I remember a group
of children holding a sign: ''Please stop. If you give us eight
minutes, we'll give you eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, we did stop, we did listen. And what an eight years it's
been! I'm proud to stand here at this extraordinary moment -- the
most peaceful, prosperous, promising time in our nation's
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's endorsement of Gore was crafted to get the party
juices flowing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've worked closely together for eight years now. In the most
difficult days of the last years, when we faced the toughest issues
-- of war and peace, of taking on powerful special interests -- he
was always there.''
</P>
<P>
   With a swipe at Bush, he added, ''To those who say the progress
of the last eight years was an accident, that we just coasted
along, let's be clear: America's success was not a matter of
chance. It was a matter of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton basked in applause after he finished his 41-minute
speech. Strains of ''Don't stop thinking about tomorrow,'' - the
theme song of his 1992 campaign, filled the hall. Delegates clapped
and waved signs that read, ''Thank you President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The convention began with an invocation that must have been
jarring for the majority of delegates who favor abortion rights.
''In you, oh God, we trust ... that you will keep us ever committed
to protect the life and well-being of all people, but especially
unborn children,'' prayed Catholic Cardinal Roger Mahony.
</P>
<P>
   In a postscript to pre-convention controversy over a fundraiser
at the Playboy Mansion, Rep. Loretta Sanchez of California visited
the hall after turning down a speaking slot for Tuesday. Under
pressure from party officials, she had agreed previously to move
the fund-raiser, and said she didn't want to give the impression
she had done so for ''personal gain.''
</P>
<P>
   The pre-convention polls were muddled. One suggested Bush's lead
had shrunk to three percentage points, but others made it a
double-digit lead. CNN said more Americans are concerned with a
candidate's stand on the issues than about character -- a switch
from the primaries of earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, Gore campaigned in Independence, home to the
political patron saint to underdogs, Harry Truman. It was there, as
well, that Lyndon Johnson signed legislation creating Medicare in
1965. ''I won't stop fighting until all our families have the
quality health care and the secure retirements they deserve,'' the
vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Gore have competing plans for Social Security, and Bush
has yet to lay out details of a plan to offer prescription drug
coverage under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   There was grumbling among some Gore strategists that the
president's four-night stay in the convention city complicated
Gore's efforts to establish his own identity for the campaign
ahead. It was the fourth convention address for the one-time
governor of Arkansas. Twelve years ago, he placed Michael Dukakis'
name in nomination in an overlong speech that drew widespread
ridicule. By 1992, he was the nominee, the ''Man from Hope'' who
was leading his party to the White House. In 1996, he spoke at
length about the ''bridge to the 21st century'' as he campaigned
toward a second term.
</P>
<P>
   Now his role was different.
</P>
<P>
   A look back at his accomplishments, a vision for the future,
and, finally, yielding the spotlight to his longtime vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Gore appear together in Michigan on Tuesday in a
ceremonial passing of the torch from one party leader to the other.
The vice president arrives in his convention city Wednesday, hours
before his formal nomination by delegates won in the primaries of
winter and spring.
</P>
<P>
   He delivers his acceptance speech Thursday, and he and Lieberman
depart shortly afterward for their first post-convention campaign
stop in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   From the convention podium, Democrats lost little time in
beginning their counter-argument to claims posted by Bush in his
Republican convention address.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Gore have led the nation to its ''longest and
strongest economic boom'' in history, said Labor Secretary Alexis
Herman in remarks prepared for delivery. Referring to claims that
Democrats had ''squandered'' their opportunity to lead, she said,
''Opportunities lost? Try memories lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The economy was ''on its knees'' when Democrats moved into the
White House in 1993, she said. The only regret, she added, was they
didn't take over sooner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 0136 </TRAILER>
