<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York delegation can't get enough of the Clintons  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) - New York's corner of the Democratic
Convention hall was the place to be Monday night as the state's
U.S. Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton took center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Roaring wildly during the first lady's speech, several New
Yorkers then wiped away tears as President Bill Clinton wound up
his own farewell address.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were a lot of wet eyes, mine among them,'' said state
party leader Michael Schell. ''We all hate to see him go. He's been
a good friend to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   But New Yorkers raved that though they were losing one Clinton
they were gaining another.
</P>
<P>
   Waving navy placards that read ''New York Loves Hillary'' and
''Give 'em Hill'' the 294 delegates from the first lady's adopted
home state used just about any pause in the first lady's speech to
cheer and chant her name.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was magnificent. She is a New Yorker through and
through,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel, the dean of the state's
Congressional delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Media also swarmed the New Yorkers to gather reaction. One
television camera angling for a shot on the crammed floor knocked a
female spectator in the head. She watched the rest of the speeches
with an ice pack nearly the size of a basketball balanced on her
head.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to comment she laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've almost been knocked out by the media, I am not giving
interviews now,'' she said, declining to provide her name.
</P>
<P>
   Supermodel and New York delegate Christie Brinkley roamed about
with a hand-held video camera capturing the goings on for Good
Morning America.
</P>
<P>
   And there was dancing in the aisle when Clinton took the stage
to the strains of ''New York, New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, hoarse from a day of speeches, lauded the
first lady for staying focused on the issues and shying away from
direct attacks on her Republican opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was both a valedictory, saying goodbye as first lady, and
the passing of the torch to the Senate campaign,'' Schumer said.
</P>
<P>
   Other delegates agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought the first lady's speech was very clear. She's not
the first lady any more, she's a candidate for the United States
Senate from New York,'' said Louis Thompson, a delegate from
Buffalo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
