<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sub Accident Highlights Russia Woes  </HEADLINE>
By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The accident that sent one of Russia's newest
nuclear subs to the sea bottom was the latest proof of how deep its
once-powerful military had sank since the Soviet collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of resources and motivation, delayed wages, corruption,
draft-dodging, hazing and other woes have plagued the poorly
financed army for years since the empire that fed it fell into
pieces in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's continuing economic disarray has only added to the army
miseries while the long-awaited military reform remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian army was humiliated by Chechen separatists in the
1994-96 war and its current campaign in Chechnya, a tiny southern
republic in the Caucasus Mountains, shows no signs of a quick
ending.
</P>
<P>
   That should not come as a surprise. Cut down from some 5 million
to about 1 million servicemen, the Russian military has to operate
on an annual budget of $5 billion, compared to the U.S. defense
spending of $280 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Air Force says it had not received a new plane since
1992 and does not expect any new aircraft until 2001. Some experts
warn that even the 6,000 nuclear warheads, Russia's primary claim
to the status of a world power, might soon become obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   The navy, now in the focus of attention over the Kursk submarine
accident, has mostly sent its ships on short training runs near
their bases due to the lack of funds to buy fuel. It also had
decommissioned hundreds of ships in the 1990s because it couldn't
afford repairs and maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Russian reports say 70 percent of navy ships need repairs. The
cash-poor navy is said to keep only three nuclear submarines on
patrol at any given time out of a force that numbered more than 100
vessels a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   One Russian navy commander, Rear Adm. Nikolai Konorev, even said
in a recent newspaper interview that if the funding shortages
continue at the current level, the navy could go out of existence
by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   The navy, and the military in general, are pinning their hopes
on President Vladimir Putin, a former Soviet KGB operative who has
insisted repeatedly on the need to restore Russia's global clout
and military might.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has reportedly boosted military spending, and has approved
a program to develop and purchase sophisticated weaponry so as to
revive conventional forces.
</P>
<P>
   ''The army has been underfinanced for several years, which has
entailed negative consequences for the nation's defense
potential,'' Putin said at the time. ''It has raised doubts about
the very possibility for Russia to have a modern army equipped with
state-of-the-art weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The encouraged navy chief, Adm. Vladimir Kuroyedov, last month
announced plans to send Russia's only aircraft carrier and several
other ships to the Mediterranean in the largest such deployment
since the Soviet times.
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk, which went down to the Barents Sea floor during major
exercises of Russia's Northern Fleet, was to be part of the
Mediterranean grouping along with five other submarines, according
to the Internet newspaper Vesti.Ru.
</P>
<P>
   ''The maneuvers, planned as a gala report to the president about
the navy's readiness to resume combat patrols in the Mediterranean,
ended with a submarine accident,'' Vesti.Ru said gloomily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
