<HEADLINE> Freight Train Derails in Montana  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALTA, Mont. (AP) -- Six tanker cars of a westbound Burlington
Northern Santa Fe freight train, three of them containing a
poisonous chemical, derailed east of Malta on Monday night, closing
U.S. Route 2 and forcing evacuations of up to 400 residents, a
railway official said.
</P>
<P>
   Initial reports were that none of the chemicals leaked from the
100-car train traveling from Memphis, Tenn., to Pasco, Wash. Sparks
from the derailing trail created small fires for several miles.
</P>
<P>
   BNFS spokesman Gus Melonas said three of the tankers contain
carbon disulphide, a poisonous, highly flammable chemical used in
making solvent and cellophane.
</P>
<P>
   Two other tankers contain titanium dioxide and pose no threat to
the environment, Melonas said. The sixth car, containing glue,
remained upright, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Malta, in north-central Montana, is about 50 miles south of the
Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   Melonas said the requested evacuation was a precaution and
involved from 200 to 400 people. A railroad emergency team rushed
to the site and a special hazardous-materials firm was en route
from Helena, about 290 miles to the southwest.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know if they're releasing any fumes,'' Phillips
County Fire Chief Clark Kelly said of the derailed tanker cars.
</P>
<P>
   He said the train set fires along the right-of-way as far away
as 20 to 30 miles to the east, toward Saco, and train personnel
were fighting them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
