<HEADLINE> West Nile pellets applied in Broome County  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) - Broome County health officials launched
an assault on the larvae and mosquitoes carrying the West Nile
virus by planting bacteria-laced pellets in about 800 storm drains.
</P>
<P>
   Two-gram granulated doses of a bacterium known as Bacillus
Sphaericus, were applied Monday in the sewer systems to kill the
larvae of two species of mosquitoes that have the potential to
harbor the virus, which can cause encephalitis and meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   The Broome County Health Department contracted Acme, a Tompkins
County-based company, to drop the larvicide into 1,200 sewers in
parts of Binghamton, Johnson City and the Town of Dickinson.
</P>
<P>
   The use of pellets is considered less toxic than spraying.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in upstate communities have begun looking at organic
pesticide options.
</P>
<P>
   The Town Board in West Seneca near Buffalo is trying to come up
with alternatives to Scourge, Anvil and Malathion, chemical
treatments used to kill adult mosquitoes that can carry the
potentially fatal virus.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is transmitted by mosquitoes through bites.
</P>
</TEXT>
