<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegates From 1960 Return  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE ARRILLAGA
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- One was a delegate, another the daughter of a
delegate. There was a politician's wife, and a Cabinet member's
assistant.
</P>
<P>
   They had gathered in Los Angeles to bear witness to history: a
raucous Democratic convention with no clear front-runner, no
scripted schedule.
</P>
<P>
   A few had seen it before; others were newcomers to the
rough-and-tumble of politics. But when John F. Kennedy stepped up
to accept the nomination and lay the 1960 Democratic National
Convention to rest, it was a moment seared in the memories of those
who were there.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, wrinkled and graying, they've returned to Los
Angeles for the encore. The scene is more sedate, the process less
spontaneous -- but these delegates will always have 1960.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a new world,'' says former Rhode Island Gov. Bruce
Sundlun, 80, who in 1960 served as special assistant to the U.S.
attorney general. His job at the convention was ''principal
gofer,'' until he was unexpectedly recruited for another task.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was sitting quietly in my seat when some young man came up
to me and said, 'Is your name Sundlun? Are you a pilot?'''
</P>
<P>
   The stranger produced a walkie-talkie -- fairly sophisticated
technology in those days -- and frantically asked whether Sundlun
could untangle the garble coming across. When Sundlun assured him
he could, the man said: ''Well, Bobby Kennedy sent me for you. He
needs you right away. Come on!''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Sundlun went from flunky to Kennedy fix-it guy. He
spent the next few days adjusting frequencies and schooling
Kennedy's floor managers on how to use the radios. And, yes, he
even met Bobby Kennedy, who was managing his brother's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Sundlun, Bethine Church was an insider from the start.
She was sitting front and center when her husband, then-U.S. Sen.
Frank Church, delivered the keynote address at the 1960 convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was so exciting all the time, but also very
nerve-racking,'' says Church, who at 77 has returned this year as
chairwoman of the Idaho delegation.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, she'll be at the microphone at the Staples
Center -- to cast Idaho's 23 votes on nominating night. She's still
working on her speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want it to be good,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Aasen wasn't even a delegate, only the daughter of a
delegate, when she happened to see John F. Kennedy in a parking lot
at the 1960 convention -- lobbying Wyoming's delegates for their
votes.
</P>
<P>
   ''That wasn't a contest, it was a battle,'' Aasen recalls of the
nomination tug-of-war among Kennedy, Lyndon Johnson and Adlai
Stevenson. ''It was a war, and you had people fighting hard for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 70, Aasen is the Democratic town committee chairwoman in
Westport, Conn., and experiencing her first convention as an
official delegate. The only thing she expects to outdo the
intensity of 1960 is security.
</P>
<P>
   What Aasen witnessed behind-the-scenes, Mike Vinich experienced
firsthand. Vinich, one of 15 Wyoming delegates in 1960, will never
forget the night his state cast the votes that put Kennedy over the
top.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were all split up,'' Vinich, now 76, recalls. ''There were
Kennedy delegates and Johnson delegates and Adlai Stevenson men. We
were all over the board.''
</P>
<P>
   As they called the roll of the states, several passed. When they
finally got to Wyoming, Kennedy needed 13 votes to win the
nomination, but the delegation was undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our guys ran around and talked to everybody. Then the chairman
got up and said, 'Wyoming gives its 15 votes to the next president
of the United States, John Kennedy.' And down came all the
balloons.
</P>
<P>
   ''The convention just went wild. What a moment!''
</P>
<P>
   This is Vinich's first convention since.
</P>
<P>
   Sundlun, a veteran of more conventions than he can remember,
responds with a resounding ''No!'' when asked whether the 2000
Democratic convention could possibly compare with 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's all a package,'' he says. ''I think the Kennedy era,
short as it was, was the last time there was any real respect for
government. It's a new world; let's move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Sundlun admits: ''Oh, sure, it's fun to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Associated Press writers Dennis Patterson and
Adam Gorlick contributed to this story.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 0241 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000815.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
