<HEADLINE> Bush Fund Raising Nears $100M Mark  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN SOLOMON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- George W. Bush is the first $100 million man
of politics.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor will report to the government later this
month that he has moved within reach of that fund-raising mark, one
that was unimaginable a quarter century ago when Congress enacted
donor limits in the aftermath of Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   Making it all the more impressive, Bush reached the figure on
the strength of 350,000 different donors to his presidential
campaign in all 50 states -- three quarters of whom gave $100 or
less, his campaign told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''That really exceeds anything we've ever seen, even if you were
to put two or three presidential campaigns together,'' said Herb
Alexander, a professor emeritus at the University of Southern
California who has studied political fund-raising for four decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it shows an immense ability by Bush to raise money. It
also is evidence of the prosperity that is here now. And it shows
the desire of Republicans to win back the White House,'' Alexander
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan told AP that Bush
finished July having raised:
</P>
<P>
   --About $95 million from individuals and PACs for his primary
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   --More than $2.5 million from individuals and PACs for a special
fund he is permitted to create to pay for legal and accounting
costs in the fall election. His campaign has added to that total
this month.
</P>
<P>
   --About $2.3 million in transfers from other political
committees, interest and dividends and other sources of income.
</P>
<P>
   He continues to raise money for his legal and accounting fund,
all but assuring he'll surpass the $100 million mark by Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   ''In building this unprecedented support, Governor Bush has
reached out to new faces and new voices who previously have not
supported Republicans or who have not participated in the political
process,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush stopped raising money for his primary campaign in late July
when, like Vice President Al Gore, he accepted full taxpayer
financing for the fall election, and he already has received a
check from the U.S. Treasury for $67.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The past record for fund raising in a single presidential race
belonged to Ross Perot, who took in $72.8 million in 1992. Nearly
all of that money, however, came from his own pocket instead of
donors.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's watershed fund raising can be traced to a decision he
made early in the 1999-2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a self-financed challenge from Republican millionaire
Steve Forbes, Bush declined the partial federal aid he was entitled
to during the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he was exempted from the spending limits imposed on
other candidates and free to raise as much as he could.
</P>
<P>
   The only restriction was he could accept no more than $1,000
from each individual and no more than $5,000 from political action
committees, the donating arms of special interests.
</P>
<P>
   There were no six-figure donations from corporations, labor
unions or wealthy executives
</P>
<P>
   Bush's take far surpasses the performance of President Clinton,
the Democrats' most prolific fund-raiser. In his two elections
combined, Clinton raised only about $66 million in individual and
PAC donations while accepting federal funding.
</P>
<P>
   It also triples Vice President Al Gore's fund raising. Gore
raised $34 million in donations through June 30 for his primary
campaign, but got another $14.6 million from the government because
he agreed to the spending limits and was eligible for partial
federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush will be on even ground in the fall because each is
limited to spending the $67.6 million in federal aid they accepted
to take them through Election Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 0249 </TRAILER>
