<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'The Opportunists'  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTY LEMIRE
For The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you get the opportunity to see ''The Opportunists,'' you may
want to pass.
</P>
<P>
   The film features some strong performances and a detailed sense
of place, but it's slow and based on a hackneyed premise.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Walken plays an ex-con named Vic Kelly, who's trying
to go straight as an auto mechanic in Queens, New York. All he
wants to do is provide a decent life for his grown daughter (Vera
Farmiga) and elderly aunt (Anne Pitoniak).
</P>
<P>
   Vic's not doing a very good job, though. He writes bad checks
all over town and he's about to get evicted for failing to pay the
rent on his garage, where he's not exactly the world's greatest
mechanic. His girlfriend Sally (Cyndi Lauper, looking surprisingly
subtle with only hair color and natural makeup) offers to lend him
the money she's saved to renovate the bar she owns, but Vic's too
proud to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   But when a fresh-faced young man named Michael (Peter McDonald)
shows up at his front door, claiming to be his cousin from Ireland
and fawning over Vic's reputation as an expert safecracker, it's
hard not to get sucked back into the life.
</P>
<P>
   Michael, along with two of Vic's buddies from the neighborhood
(Donal Logue and Jose Zuniga) who are stuck in low-paying jobs as
security guards, persuade Vic to perform the infamous ''one last
heist.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, this idea isn't terribly original -- we've seen it three
times this year alone. Nicolas Cage played an ex-con forced to pull
off one last car heist in ''Gone in 60 Seconds.'' Paul Newman
played an ex-con forced to pull off one last armored car heist in
''Where the Money Is.'' Ben Affleck played an ex-con forced to pull
off one last casino heist in ''Reindeer Games.''
</P>
<P>
   It's familiar territory, for sure, but first-time
writer-director Myles Connell's pacing is so slow it seems to take
forever to reach our destination. Once we get there, he creates
little suspense.
</P>
<P>
   Connell, a Dublin native who says the Michael character is
semi-autobiographical, does get the details right in the
blue-collar Queens setting. The modest row houses, Vic's run-down
garage and Sally's neighborhood tavern have an authentic feel. It
helps that Walken and Lauper are originally from Queens -- they show
a comfort with the location and the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Opportunists'' is a good chance for Walken to play the
lead once again after years of supporting roles in films including
''Batman Returns,'' ''Pulp Fiction'' and ''Blast from the Past.''
The film is boring at times, but his performance never is. He is
totally believable as a man torn between an honest life and the
temptation of quick, easy cash.
</P>
<P>
   As Vic's daughter, Farmiga also is a joy to watch. She brings a
sweetness and naturalness to her role.
</P>
<P>
   But no one in the cast can keep Logue from stealing every scene
he's in. Logue was so good recently as a chubby Casanova in the
indie hit ''The Tao of Steve,'' and again shows charm and ease on
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Opportunists,'' a First Look Pictures release, appeared at
this year's Sundance Film Festival. Jonathan Demme is one of the
five executive producers. The film is rated R for language. Running
time: 89 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 0927 </TRAILER>
