<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 76; Nasdaq Adds 4  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were on Tuesday as investors sold off
blue chips after three straight winning sessions. The Nasdaq inched
up slightly.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 75.72 to 11,099.41, after a 148-point
surge yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 2.92 to 1,488.64. The
Nasdaq composite index was up 3.68 to 3,853.37.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were focusing on a host of retail companies that were
reporting earnings. Those included Dow component Home Depot, which
met Wall Street forecasts. The stock which had risen 6 percent
earlier this week, fell $4.50 to $55.
</P>
<P>
   Drugmakers, which have benefitted from many investors' turn
toward defensive stocks that can better withstand an economic
downturn, were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb, which made a legal maneuver Tuesday which
seems to temporarily preserve its patent protection on its
blockbuster cancer drug Taxol, rose $2.75 to $55.375. Generic
drugmaker Ivax, which was poised to start making a cheaper, generic
Taxol, plunged $9.375 to $33.
</P>
<P>
   On the economic front, the Federal Reserve said industrial
production rose 0.4 percent in July, in line with analysts'
expectations. The report contained little sign of inflation, which
should make investors more confident the central bank will leave
interest rates unchanged when it convenes next week.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 115.12 million
shares, up from Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 0.93 to 513.55.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.89 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.33 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.54 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.54 percent.
</P>
