<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 124; Nasdaq Sheds 5  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned lower Tuesday, as investors sold
off blue chips after three straight winning sessions. Technology
issues slipped.
</P>
<P>
   At midmorning on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average
was down 123.89 to 11,053.78, after a 148-point surge on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 5.44 to 1,486.12. The
Nasdaq composite index was down 4.55 to 3,854.24.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said profit taking was largely responsible for Dow's
drop.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were focusing on a host of retail companies that were
reporting earnings. Those included Dow component Home Depot, which
met Wall Street forecasts. The stock which had risen 6 percent
earlier this week, fell $4.50 to $55.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Penney dropped $1.25 to $16.673 after reporting that its
second-quarter profit dropped 90 percent due to lower sales and
price cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Drugmakers, which have benefitted from many investors' turn
toward defensive stocks that can better withstand an economic
downturn, were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb, which made a legal maneuver Tuesday that
seems to temporarily preserve its patent protection on its
blockbuster cancer drug Taxol, rose $2.75 to $55.375. Generic
drugmaker Ivax, which was poised to start making a cheaper, generic
Taxol, plunged $9.375 to $33.
</P>
<P>
   Among technology stocks, JDS Uniphase fell $1 to $119.25 and
Radio Shack dropped $4 to $65.
</P>
<P>
   On the economic front, the Federal Reserve said industrial
production rose 0.4 percent in July, in line with analysts'
expectations. The report contained little sign of inflation, which
should make investors more confident the central bank will leave
interest rates unchanged when it convenes next week.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 5-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 287.45 million
shares, up from Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 1.47 to 513.01.
</P>
