<HEADLINE> Spanish Cops Blow Up Abandoned Car  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUESCA, Spain (AP) -- Spanish police used a robot Tuesday to blow
up a car that had been packed with 220 pounds of explosives and
abandoned on a highway.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the vehicle may have been intended for use in a car
bomb attack. Police said they had no suspects, but have blamed the
Basque separatist group ETA for several car bombs. Last week, four
suspected ETA members died when explosives blew up in their car.
</P>
<P>
   Police sealed off a 12-mile stretch of highway near Huesca at
the foot of the Pyrenees Mountains before blowing up the Renault on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had received calls from motorists about an abandoned
car and decided to blow it up after they discovered it had stolen
license plates. An investigation wreckage determined the car had
been loaded with explosives, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ETA's armed drive for an independent homeland carved out of
parts of northern Spain and southern France has claimed nearly 800
lives since it began in 1968. ETA is the acronym for Basque
Homeland and Freedom in the Basque language.
</P>
</TEXT>
