<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea Frees 3,586 Prisoners  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korea freed 3,586 inmates from
prisons across the country Tuesday in a sweeping amnesty ordered by
President Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
   They included Chung Soo Il, 63, a North Korean spy who had posed
as a college professor. Chung was arrested in 1998 and sentenced to
12 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Those freed Tuesday were among 30,647 people who benefited from
the amnesty, which marked the anniversary of Korea's liberation
from Japan's 35-year colonial rule on Aug. 15, 1945.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 23,730 people, who were already out of prison after
serving time for minor offenses, had their civil rights reinstated,
which means they can run for election and vote again, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was Kim Hyun-chul, 41-year-old son of former
President Kim Young-sam, who served six months in prison in 1996 on
corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   Hong In-kil, an aide to the ex-president arrested on corruption
charges in 1997, was also freed Tuesday. He was serving a six-year
prison term.
</P>
<P>
   Several human rights activists protested Hong's release,
engaging in a shoving match with Hong's followers outside the
prison north of Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Activists complained the government was releasing corrupt
politicians while about 120 ''prisoners of conscience,'' mostly
student and labor activists convicted of violent protests, remained
in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
