<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Leader Backs Off Promise  </HEADLINE>
By SLOBODAN LEKIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's push for democracy ran
into new hurdles Tuesday when President Abdurrahman Wahid backed
off promises to empower his untested but popular deputy and the
legislature prepared to extend the military's political role.
</P>
<P>
   A decree drafted by a committee within the People's Consultative
Assembly would allow the armed forces to retain their 38 seats in
the 700-member body until 2009. The full assembly is expected to
pass the measure Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid diluted his promise to put Vice President Megawati
Sukarnoputri in charge of day-to-day operations in the Cabinet,
saying she could only make decisions in consultation with him and
two senior ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Following an impeachment threat by legislators angered at the
disarray in his 10-month-old government, Wahid last week announced
he would surrender domestic administrative duties to his vice
president, who heads Indonesia's largest political party.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he told the assembly he would henceforth
concentrate on foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear how Wahid's reversal would be
greeted by lawmakers, who have proposed codifying the vice
president's new authority. Assembly members have severely
criticized the president's administrative style and the lack of
progress in reviving Indonesia's ailing economy.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the assembly effectively postponed consideration of
constitutional amendments until next year. These include proposals
to introduce Islamic law for Indonesia's Muslims and to allow
direct presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 Muslim protesters rallied outside the assembly
building Tuesday to demand the imposition of Muslim law.
</P>
<P>
   The full assembly seems virtually certain to approve a continued
role in politics for the military, which underpinned the 32-year
dictatorship of former president Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Accused of widespread human rights abuses, the army's top brass
had seen a steady decline in influence since the legislature last
year elected Wahid, the country's first freely chosen leader in
four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators have justified the military's role by saying that
the 500,000-strong armed forces had a right to representation,
although it was not allowed to vote in the assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a real setback for Indonesia's transformation to
democracy,'' said Smita Notosusanto, a political science professor
and analyst at the non-governmental Center for Electoral Reform.
''All members of the legislature have to be elected, not
appointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some legislators have said they are being railroaded by powerful
generals who threaten to foment trouble in strife-torn Aceh, Maluku
and West Papua provinces unless they are allowed to retain a
political role.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 1229 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000815.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Starts Hearing Sharif Appeal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) -- Deposed prime minister Nawaz Sharif
began an appeal of his hijacking and terrorism conviction Tuesday,
saying Pakistan's military rulers had intimidated witnesses against
him.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif was sentenced to two concurrent life terms on the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif was convicted in April by an anti-terrorist court for
preventing the landing of a passenger plane that was returning Army
Chief Gen. Pervez Musharraf to Pakistan from Sri Lanka as
Musharraf's soliders were conducting a coup Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was eventually allowed to land after the army took
control of the airport. When it landed there was barely seven
minutes of fuel remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's lawyer Azizullah Sheikh told the Sindh High Court on
Tuesday that there were glaring contradictions in the testimonies
of the three key witnesses against Sharif. He said that the
witnesses had been intimidated by the military.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal had been delayed for weeks while Sharif's lawyers
filed a motion to dismiss over legal jurisdiction -- an argument
they lost.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's six co-defendants were acquitted in the original trial.
Sharif has also been disqualified from politics for 21 years and
last month was sentenced to 14 years in jail last month for tax
evasion.
</P>
<P>
   If he loses this appeal, Sharif can make a final appeal to the
Supreme Court. The prosecution also is appealing, demanding Sharif
be given the death penalty instead of life in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
