<HEADLINE> China Gives Dissident Early Release  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Without explanation, China has unexpectedly
knocked 20 months off a pro-democracy campaigner's 10-year jail
term and released him, a human rights group said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Liu Wensheng, 32, was freed Aug. 9 from a prison in the
northwestern Chinese province of Gansu and has returned home to the
city of Yinchuan in the neighboring province of Ningxia, the
Information Center for Human Rights and Democracy said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong-based group said Liu was arrested in April 1992
and sentenced to 10 years for organizing the Social Democratic
Party of China, a dissident group opposed to the ruling Communist
Party's monopoly on power.
</P>
<P>
   Liu was not due for release until April 2002. Prison authorities
did not tell Liu why they were releasing him early, the center
said.
</P>
