<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Reformers Protect Free Press  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- In a daring move after an order from Iran's
supreme leader to drop a debate on press freedoms, reformist
lawmakers presented a bill Tuesday that aims to block the hard-line
judiciary from closing reformist newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators submitted an ''extremely urgent'' motion to the
parliament, or Majlis, seeking a debate on whether it was legal to
close newspapers under the Security Measures Law, the official
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) quoted a lawmaker as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ''Several courts have closed the dailies on the basis of this
law ... and clarification in this case would remove many
ambiguities, including those involving the press,'' IRNA quoted
legislator Gholam Heidar Ebrahimbai Salami as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Salami said speaker Mahdi Karrubi refused to acknowledge receipt
of the bill, but did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The reformist-dominated parliament vowed top pursue reforms in a
letter Sunday addressed to the nation and signed by 161 members.
</P>
<P>
   ''Reforms are not the monopoly of anybody. It is a national
demand,'' Abbas Abdi, a leading reformist journalist, told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''And reforms are meaningless without press freedoms. Reformists
should employ a new method to deal with the illegal closure of
newspapers by the judiciary in order to fulfill their promises,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers were to discuss a bill last Sunday to lift
restrictions imposed on the press by their hard-line predecessors.
But supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei intervened and instructed
the deputies not to amend the press law, causing scuffles, shouts
and a fight in open session.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-liners suffered their worst political defeat in February
legislative elections, when they lost control of the house for the
first time since the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hard-liners' last undertakings in the previous
session was to push through a press law that has been the basis for
a ban on 25 publications -- all but one of them pro-reform
newspapers -- and the arrest of two dozen writers.
</P>
<P>
   Hard-liners have lost considerable power since President
Mohammad Khatami, a reformist, was elected in 1997. But they retain
control of the judiciary, the military and the broadcast network.
They are backed by Khamenei, who has the last say on all matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 1447 </TRAILER>
