<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians May Not Proclaim State  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The Palestinians dropped new hints that Yasser
Arafat may not proclaim a state Sept. 13, even as the Palestinian
leader continued his world tour Tuesday with stops in the Far East
to gauge support for such a unilateral move.
</P>
<P>
   Taking no chances, Israel's top diplomats, including Nobel Peace
Prize laureate Shimon Peres, stayed on Arafat's trail to try to
blunt his message.
</P>
<P>
   In Tokyo, Peres told Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori of Japan that
peace talks may break down if Arafat declares Palestinian
independence on Sept. 13, the deadline for an Israeli-Palestinian
peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's aides have said a peace deal remains his preferred
choice. Talk about proclaiming independence without Israel's
blessing appears to be mainly an attempt to create leverage in
negotiations. A disjointed state in parts of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip would not be viable, even if recognized by some countries.
</P>
<P>
   The PLO Central Council, the Palestine Liberation Organization's
129-member policy-making body, is to convene Sept. 8 or 9 in Gaza
City to discuss a date for independence. In July, the council told
Palestinians to prepare for independence by Sept. 13, but did not
require Arafat to issue a proclamation on that date.
</P>
<P>
   In the upcoming meeting, council members ''will evaluate the
situation ... and decide what is suitable for the Palestinians,''
said Palestinian peace negotiator Ahmed Qureia, who is close to
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Qureia, the speaker of the Palestinian parliament, made no
reference to the Sept. 13 date, saying only that ''I don't imagine
that we will pass this year without a declaration of state which we
hope will deserve the recognition of all the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In Arafat's three-week diplomatic offensive -- he has visited 18
countries on three continents -- Arafat failed to win broad backing
for a unilateral declaration of statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Most European Union countries have advised the Palestinian
leader not to do anything to endanger negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin, who spoke by phone with
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak about Mideast peacemaking on
Tuesday, has also counseled Arafat not to make a unilateral
declaration.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has picked up some support in the Far East. In Beijing,
he was told Monday that China would support any Palestinian
decision, and in a Tuesday stopover in Kuala Lumpur he was assured
that Malaysia would recognize a state declared Sept. 13. The next
stops on his itinerary are Japan and Indonesia, where Peres has
already briefed leaders on the Israeli position.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid said Tuesday that the
deadlock over Jerusalem, which led to the breakdown of the Mideast
summit at Camp David, could be resolved by rethinking the concept
of sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Israel should be given administrative sovereignty, while a
seven-member committee with representatives from Egypt, Jordan,
Syria, Lebanon, Israel, the United Nations and the Palestinians
would have political sovereignty, Wahid said.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is unlikely the proposal will be considered because
both Israel and the Palestinians are reluctant to share control
over the city with others.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli peace negotiator Shlomo Ben-Ami, who returned to Israel
on Tuesday after a tour of European capitals, said Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators are now trying to lay the groundwork for a
second summit.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators first will have to put together a U.S.-backed
''pre-agreement'' that will include understandings reached in the
previous two-week round of talks at Camp David, Ben-Ami said.
</P>
<P>
   If everything falls into place, a summit can be held in
September, the negotiator said, adding that no date has been set.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 1513 </TRAILER>
