<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest in German Parliament Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Fred Gebhardt, Germany's oldest member
of parliament, who left the Social Democrats to protest their move
to the center and joined the former East German communist party,
has died at 72.
</P>
<P>
   The Party of Democratic Socialism's branch in Hesse state said
Tuesday that Gebhardt had died the previous night after a long
illness.
</P>
<P>
   Gebhardt left the Social Democrats, the party of Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder, in 1998 after 52 years in protest against the
left-wing party's shift toward the center, which he termed a change
in course ''from an employees' to a neo-liberal business party.''
</P>
<P>
   He had also served as Hesse's Social Democratic chairman, based
in Frankfurt, where he headed an adult education school.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1998, he was elected to the Bundestag, or lower
house, for the former communists and gave the speech opening
parliament, traditionally delivered by the oldest legislator. He
also served on the human rights committee.
</P>
<P>
   Gebhardt is survived by two daughters. Funeral plans were not
immediately announced.
</P>
</TEXT>
