<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge dismisses defamation suit against Koch for 'People's Court' comments </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Manhattan judge has dismissed a lawsuit by a
man who claims that he was defamed when former Mayor Edward I. Koch
called him a ''kidnapper'' on ''The People's Court'' television
show.
</P>
<P>
   Civil Court Judge Norman Ryp said state law makes Koch, as the
show's ''judge'' in an arbitration the parties agreed to in
writing, ''absolutely immune from liability for all acts within the
arbitral process.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, at least the second against Koch while he was on
the show, was filed by Idris Kabia, a native of Sierra Leone,
Africa, who appeared on the program that was videotaped Feb. 9,
1999, and televised in March.
</P>
<P>
   Ryp said he viewed edited and unedited versions of the show and
read transcripts of the programs but could find no reference to
Idris's alleged kidnapping of his then-young son fron Sierra Leone
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The show arose from a Small Claims Court lawsuit for $2,000 that
Kabia had filed against his son, Ahmed Kabia. The elder Kabia had
accused his son of failing to return some photos of the two of them
together.
</P>
<P>
   Before the show was taped, parties on both sides signed a
contract with Ralph Edwards Productions, the show's producers. They
agreed that the production company - not the loser - will pay the
winner. If no award is made by the show's judge, then each party
gets $250 just for appearing.
</P>
<P>
   The parties also agreed that Koch and the producers are released
from liability for remarks during the show that either side
believes to be ''derogatory, defamatory or in some other way
injurious to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   At the show's conclusion, Koch found in favor of the son but
awarded neither side any money. Kabia received, and deposited, a
$250 check from the producer and an edited version of the show
aired nationally in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1999, Kabia sued, alleging Koch said things that
''defame, libel and slander'' him. Ryp said the only issue for
trial was whether Koch said the words ''kidnapped'' or
''kidnapper'' with reference to Kabia.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no recollection of saying that,'' Koch said when
reached at his office. ''But even if it (the videotape) contained
the commentary that he alleged, he still couldn't sue, by
agreement''
</P>
<P>
   Ryp suggested that even if he had been able to find a reference
to Kabia as a kidnapper, he had signed a contract releasing Koch
and the program's producers from anything said on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Koch left the show in 1999, replaced by retired State Supreme
Court Justice Jerry Scheindlin. Koch recalled that he appointed
both Scheindlin and his wife, ''Judge Judy'' Scheindlin, to their
first judicial jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're doing terrific jobs and I enjoy watching them,'' Koch
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-15-00 1621 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000815.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
