<HEADLINE> Losing thoroughbred Zippy Chippy takes his act to the baseball field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Zippy Chippy has a 50-50 chance of
actually winning a race this week. The competition: a fleet-footed,
minor-league baseball player.
</P>
<P>
   The losingest horse in the recorded history of U.S. thoroughbred
racing will line up for a 40-yard dash against Jose Herrera, the
base-stealing center fielder for the Rochester Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   The ''2000 Red Wings Derby'' was set for Thursday evening before
the Red Wings' game against Scranton/Wilkes Barre. Herrera, 27, has
stolen 155 bases in his 10-year professional career, including 10
for the Red Wings this season.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-year-old gelding, 0-for-86 in his career, has been banned
from competition at the Finger Lakes racetrack in nearby Farmington
and, because of reciprocal agreements, just about everywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Zippy Chippy set the record with his 86th loss last September
when he came in third in a field of six at a county fair in
Northampton, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
