<HEADLINE> Business news in brief from around New Jersey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OAK RIDGE, N.J. (AP) - Lakeland Bancorp on Tuesday announced a
new flood disaster loan program aimed at residents of northwestern
New Jersey whose properties were damaged by recent heavy rains and
flooding.
</P>
<P>
   The Oak Ridge-based corporation is the holding company for
Lakeland Bank and The National Bank of Sussex County, which
together operate about two dozen bank branches in Sussex, Morris,
Passaic, Hunterdon and Bergen counties.
</P>
<P>
   The banks will offer reduced-rate home equity loans with no
fees. Interested homeowners should contact the local branch of
either bank for details.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Bosma, president and chief executive officer of Lakeland
Bancorp, said the special loans will be offered through Oct. 15 to
those whose homes sustained damage from the rain and flooding since
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   WAYNE, N.J. (AP) - In an effort to cut costs, struggling
supermarket chain Grand Union Co. is eliminating about 170 jobs,
effective immediately.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest food retailers in the Northeast, Grand Union
said the cuts announced Monday primarily involve jobs at its
headquarters here and its administrative offices in upstate New
York. In addition, some positions will be cut from its
approximately 220 supermarkets in New York, New Jersey, Vermont,
Connecticut, New Hampshire and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Union president Gary M. Philbin said the reductions were
''economically necessary'' and should reduce annual costs by $8
million to $12 million while increasing operating cash flow. The
company, which had fiscal 2000 sales of $2.2 billion, said the job
cuts will result in a charge of about $2 million for the fiscal
2001 second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The chain, which once had more than 900 stores from Florida to
Canada and west to Texas, entered bankruptcy protection twice
during the 1990s, most recently in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ROSELAND, N.J. (AP) - Automatic Data Processing Inc. said
Tuesday that its emerging business services division has formed a
partnership with EarthLink, the nation's second-largest Internet
Service Provider.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, the ADP division will provide online services to
help EarthLink's small-business customers streamline their business
processes.
</P>
<P>
   EarthLink members also will receive a trial offer to use ADP's
payroll tax services and software via ADP's ''virtual consultant,''
called Solution Profiler. Meanwhile, ADP's 370,000 small business
customers will get a special offer for EarthLink Internet access,
Web site hosting and development and domain registration services.
</P>
<P>
   MADISON, N.J. (AP) - The American Heart Association has added a
new heart medication to the treatments included in its guidelines
for advanced cardiac life support, according to the drug's
manufacturer, American Home Products Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Tuesday that the guidelines, which were last
revised in 1992, will call for use of Cordarone I.V., its
medication for abnormal heart rhythms. The new guidelines are to be
published in next Tuesday's issue of the medical journal
Circulation.
</P>
<P>
   According to American Home Products, the guidelines will
recommend physicians consider giving the drug to patients whose
hearts are beating rapidly and ineffectively but do not respond to
cardiopulmonary resuscitation or defibrillation shocks - before
giving the patient another heart drug called lidocaine. Lidocaine
for years has been given to nearly every patient suffering cardiac
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent study, Cordarone I.V., made by AHP's Wyeth-Ayerst
Laboratories division, was shown to increase by 29 percent the
number of heart attack patients who survived until they reached the
hospital, the company said.
</P>
</TEXT>
