<HEADLINE> Gibraltar Nuclear Sub Protested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBRALTAR (AP) -- More than 1,500 people marched and sailed
toward a nuclear submarine Tuesday to protest the British vessel's
presence for repairs in a Gibraltar harbor.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 sailboats and motorboats sailed to within a few hundred
yards of the docked submarine HMS Tireless while crowds rallied on
land close by. Police blocked protesters from moving closer.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd sang ''Tireless Out'' -- a song written for the
demonstration -- and waved signs demanding that British authorities
tow the submarine to England for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters fear a radiation leak and say Gibraltar is not
equipped to handle such an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   British officials say the submarine has a very small coolant
leak in its propulsion system but insist there is no danger of a
radiation spill from the nuclear-powered engines.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no safety concerns,'' said ministry spokesman Jim
Jenkin. ''The level of radiation is being monitored and there has
been no increase whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   The HMS Tireless has been docked in Gibraltar since May 19.
</P>
<P>
   ''The British Ministry of Defense has not given any optimism to
dispel fears,'' said Levi Attias, a protest organizer and Gibraltar
resident. ''This is not the end of our campaign and we're
considering legal action to remove the submarine.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the protest -- coming as Russian rescuers struggle
to save 116 sailors trapped in a nuclear submarine on the ocean
floor above the Arctic Circle -- is pure coincidence, said Attias.
</P>
<P>
   However, the incidents ''show that nuclear submarines are not
toys and malfunctions are not to be played with,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, protesters gathered several thousand
signatures for a petition asking the Gibraltar government to push
for the submarine's removal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
