<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio stumps for votes on the No. 7 train, Queens  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - No, that wasn't John Rocker riding the No. 7
train on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Trailed by a throng of media, Republican Senate candidate Rick
Lazio rode the subway from Manhattan to Queens for a campaign trip
through Flushing. He greeted well-wishers along Roosevelt Avenue
and later threw a few ''knock-down'' pitches at his Democratic
opponent -- Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who had no speaking role and made a one-day cameo at the
Republican National Convention two weeks ago, jabbed at the first
lady's speech Monday night at the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought that she had the opportunity to focus on New York a
little bit and New York's issues and it just seemed like she was
more interested in running for national office than senator from
New York,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added later, ''I just think she's out of touch with what
regular New Yorkers feel and experience and need.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathie Levine, a Clinton spokeswoman, countered that had the
congressman spent more time at the GOP convention,''I'm sure Rick
Lazio would have made a very different kind of speech, one that
obscures his record of voting for a real and enforcible Patient's
Bill of Rights and against putting 100,000 new teachers in our
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Clinton ''chose to talk about the importance of
electing Al Gore and Joe Lieberman, the progress the administration
has made over the last eight years and the works she has done on
behalf of children and family for the past 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   On the trip to Flushing, however, Lazio hardly could be mistaken
for Rocker, the notorious Atlanta Braves relief pitcher who bashed
New York City and its residents -- specifically foreigners and gays
who take the 7 train -- in a 1999 Sports Illustrated article.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, few people aboard the sparsely populated midday train
even knew who the Long Island congressman was. He received a much
more enthusiastic greeting on Roosevelt Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's loved,'' said Mary Anderson of Bayside. ''He's a suburban
man, he's a city man, he's a family man. He knows New York. He's
fought for the people ... he's down to earth and he'll buck anybody
that does not do good for his people in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanda Antosh conceded that Lazio has an uphill fight against
Clinton because Democrats outnumber Republicans in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has to penetrate the Democratic Party,'' she said. ''And I
think he can because he's an honest man and his principles are good
and he's genuine. He's not a phony, Hollywood person.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was trailed through Flushing by a number of protesters
--one group questioned his commitment to legalized abortion and
another repeated calls for him to release his tax returns --
something he has said he'll do by the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd be willing to release, in the next 15 minutes, all of my
New York state tax returns if she's willing to do the same,'' he
smirked and then he walked away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
