<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yale poll to track attitudes about political ads on TV  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) - They scream out at you from the TV:
political attack ads that try to paint candidates as two-faced
liars, cheats and villains.
</P>
<P>
   Such ads have become a mainstay in politics, but do they really
matter? Who pays attention? Do they affect how anyone actually
votes?
</P>
<P>
   That's what a Yale University study is trying to find out, using
an Internet-based polling system that can track the way attitudes
of respondents change over time.
</P>
<P>
   The Yale study will track the presidential race and the New York
Senate race between Hillary Rodham Clinton and Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   The polling system allows respondents to watch political ads and
answer to a series of questions about the election. Other people
will answer the same questions but will not see the ads.
</P>
<P>
   ''People think campaign commercials are highly effective, but we
don't have any research to show how effective they are,'' said Yale
political science Professor John Lapinski said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lapinski also wants to see if they can measure the effect of ads
on certain demographic groups to see if ads have more impact on
some people than on others.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say about $600 million will be spent on political ads
nationwide for the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   Some research has shown that the ads help little-known
candidates get name recognition, but do little to sway voters, said
Doug Schwartz, pollster at Quinnipiac University.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a great idea because it is so hard to test the
impact of campaign ads in the real world,'' Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
   Some ads do stick in people's minds: the Willie Horton ads that
attacked 1988 Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis as
soft on crime; the spot from the 1996 Connecticut congressional
race in which a rat crawled across the screen while U.S. Rep. Gary
Franks was attacked as a slumlord.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is hard for people to see a rat going across the screen
while they are eating their dinner and not say, 'Boy, that guy must
be terrible,''' Franks said in conceding defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The first poll results came in this week, after Vice President
Al Gore picked Connecticut Sen. Joe Lieberman to be his
running-mate, but before the Democratic National Convention got
underway.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 903 registered voters conducted between Aug. 9 and
Aug. 11 found Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush in a statistical
tie in a four-way race. Bush got 41 percent and Gore got 38 percent
- within the margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Three percent of those polled supported Green Party candidate
Ralph Nader, and less than 1 percent picked Reform Party candidate
Pat Buchanan. Seventeen percent said they were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   These results will be used as a benchmark for future surveys,
Lapinski said.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents to the poll were chosen by random telephone dialing.
People who agreed to participate were given a free Web TV account
with a hard drive so they can download commercials.
</P>
<P>
   They will receive questionnaires and other information by
e-mail. Respondents also can access the Web TV for personal use.
</P>
<P>
   Some people already were regular Internet users, while others
were not.
</P>
<P>
   The free Internet access ensures a broader sample of people, but
researchers will be looking to see whether the new presence of the
Internet changes the views of people who previously did not use
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The sample of respondents is changed from time to time so that
they do not get sick of being polled and to prevent them from
becoming, in effect, professional poll responders, Lapinski said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Kohut, the director of the Pew Research Center in
Washington, said this type in Internet-based polling will be better
for political analysis than the surveys usually done by telephone
to get a snapshot of who is leading in the race.
</P>
<P>
   The downloading of political commercials is an artificial way to
get results, since this is not something most people would probably
do on their own, Kohut said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-15-00 1739 </TRAILER>
