<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman choice praised by black scholar  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW DALY
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Joseph Lieberman will be
popular among black voters, despite some misgivings among blacks
about Lieberman's position on affirmative action, a prominent black
scholar predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, the first Jew ever chosen for a major national
ticket, is ''a person of integrity'' who has ''brought a certain
dignity to the ticket'' that will be attractive to all types of
voters, said Julius Lester, a professor of Judaic and Near Eastern
studies at the University of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Lester, who is both black and Jewish, said the media has
overstated the impact of Lieberman's religion on the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   Both Jewish and black voters will support the Democratic ticket
''overwhelmingly'' this fall, Lester said, disputing reports that
blacks tend to hold more anti-Jewish views than the population as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to remember that blacks and Jews have continued to
vote very similarly on both national and state elections around the
country, so I would certainly not expect that to change in any
way,'' Lester said.
</P>
<P>
   Lester made the comments as Lieberman and Vice President Al Gore
sought to allay concerns among some black leaders about Lieberman's
stand on affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman supported a 1998 California proposition that banned
state-funded affirmative action programs and has opposed what he
describes as racial quotas.
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman told about 300 black delegates to the Democratic
National Convention that he supports affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have supported affirmative action. I do support affirmative
action. And I will support affirmative action,'' said Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane told reporters that Lieberman has a
strong civil rights record and pointed out that Lieberman traveled
to the South in the 1960s to help register blacks to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Lester praised Lieberman's decision to meet with the black
delegates and said it showed he does not take black support for
granted. While acknowledging that most blacks disagree with
Lieberman's views on affirmative action, Lester said it would be a
mistake to assume that disagreements extend to other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the perception of the black community as being
ultraliberal is mistaken,'' Lester said, calling black voters
liberal on race but moderate or even conservative on other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's ''social conservatism and his emphasis on family
values and religiosity will play very well with the black
community,'' Lester said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's selection of the Connecticut senator has been hailed by
black leaders from Jesse Jackson to Al Sharpton. Even Nation of
Islam leader Louis Farrakhan, who once called Judaism a ''gutter
religion,'' has tempered criticism of Lieberman to make clear that
his religion should not be an issue for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Lester, the son of a Methodist minister, converted to Judaism in
1982. He said Lieberman's selection has justifiably stirred
euphoria among many Jews - including himself - but has also sparked
some fear, particularly among older Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The selection is less controversial than it would have been a
decade or even five years ago, Lester said, but added, ''We're
certainly going to find out how much latent anti-Semitism there is
in America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-15-00 1741 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000815.0113 </DOCNO>
