<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuomo says he's made decision on governor's race, McCall works crowd </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) - The road to the New York governor's mansion
goes through Los Angeles this week.
</P>
<P>
   Two potential Democratic rivals, state Comptroller H. Carl
McCall and U.S. Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, are fervently
courting New York delegates and attacking Republican Gov. George
Pataki at the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Both men used their breakfast speeches to the delegation to
attack state Republicans, but after his on Tuesday, Cuomo revealed
that he has made up his mind on whether to run for governor in
2002.
</P>
<P>
   However, he won't say what he decided. Instead, he says he wants
to keep the focus on Hillary Clinton and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But he did lead off his speech with a tribute to his home state
and then focused heavily on how upstate New York has been left
behind the nation's economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no state in the nation like New York,'' the eldest
son of former Gov. Mario Cuomo said. ''Imagine when we bring this
great economy to all the places that are untouched. When we bring
it to upstate New York ... and we reverse what the Republicans have
done.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall was unperturbed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Good for him,''' he said. ''It sounds like he's planning to
run for something. I wish him well.''
</P>
<P>
   While McCall has not said publicly what his plans are,
supporters said he has told them privately he is running. McCall,
the first black elected to statewide office in New York, has
already raised $1.4 million. As trustee of New York's $122 billion
fund he is viewed as the largest investor in the world and is
expected to have little trouble raising the $20 million his camp
estimates he would need to make the race.
</P>
<P>
   And he has been busy lining up union support.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I make an announcement about what I'm going to do, I
think the kind of overwhelming support that I have will make it
clear that anyone who wants to take me on is in for one heck of a
battle, and if they want to have that battle I'm ready,'' McCall
said.
</P>
<P>
   McCall attacked Pataki by name on Monday morning, also accusing
him ignoring the upstate economy and cutting funding for education
even as New York racked up record budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The two Democrats have been a bit like Clark Kent and Superman
at the convention. Both appear to be everywhere but never seem to
be in the same place at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Both men been fixtures in the palatial lobby of the Century
Plaza hotel where the New York delegation is staying but have never
been seen together. McCall also was nowhere to be seen during
Cuomo's speech and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo will go Hollywood Wednesday night. Actor Bill Baldwin and
his Creative Coalition will honor him with a public service award
at a reception at the Los Angeles Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that Cuomo is reaching out even to those in McCall's
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gregory Meeks of Queens said he met with the housing
secretary about a month ago and they would likely talk again.
''Although he didn't declare that he was running it was clear that
he was feeling his way around,'' Meeks said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like Andrew personally but if the election were held today I
would have to climb on board with Carl McCall,'' Meeks said.
''Whether it's Carl McCall or Andrew Cuomo what the Democratic
Party is doing is lining up a strong Democratic candidate and that
can only be good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
