<HEADLINE> At Least 4 Killed in Colombia Clash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Colombian students on a field trip were
caught in a crossfire between government troops and leftist rebels
Tuesday and at least four children were killed, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Jairo Franco, an official from the nearby town of
Pueblorrico, said four children were killed. But Dr. Helena
Restrepo of Pueblorrico's hospital, said six had died.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a lot of fierce combat. They walked right into it,''
said Martin Morales, director of the San Juan de Dios Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels were from the National Liberation Army, or ELN,
Colombia's second-largest guerrilla group, said Alfredo Salgado,
assistant director of Colombia's national police force.
</P>
<P>
   The group of children was on a trip with two of their teachers
in the mountain municipality of Pueblorrico, 150 miles northwest of
the capital, Bogota.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said the two teachers escaped unharmed. How many
children were on the trip and their ages were not immediately
known.
</P>
<P>
   Combat between Colombia's two leftist rebel armies, government
troops and police has been intense. At least 27 people have been
killed over the past day in bloody clashes between Colombian
security forces and rebels from ELN and FARC, the Revolutionary
Armed Forces of Colombia.
</P>
</TEXT>
