<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 109; Nasdaq Gains 2  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow's three-day winning streak ended Tuesday
amid a downturn among retail, brokerage and health stocks.
Meanwhile, a strong session by semiconductor issues failed to give
the lethargic Nasdaq Stock Market much of a charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average lost 109.14 to 11,067.00. That
wiped out much of the Dow's 148-point surge on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-laden Nasdaq composite index rose 1.97 to
3,851.66. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index slipped 7.13 to 1,484.43.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts blamed profit-taking for the Dow's drop. The Dow had
risen in recent days amid optimism that the Federal Reserve would
leave interest rates unchanged at its meeting next week.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's profit-taking on the Dow and a resurgence in the tech
sector due to relative opportunities in semiconductors, which have
been devastated in the past month,'' said Barry Hyman, senior
equity analyst at Ehrenkrantz King Nussbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Gains on the tech sector remained limited to a handful of
familiar names. ''People want the safety of big-cap tech stocks and
they're not fiddling with mid-tier companies,'' Hyman said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel was up 93.75 cents to $67.875 and Sun jumped $3.312 to
$117.375.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers, which have largely done well in recent weeks due to
the stabilizing interest rate environment, helped pull the market
down on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dow component Home Depot, which met Wall Street forecasts, fell
$5.938 to $53.75 after a big run-up the past two weeks. Some
analysts were concerned the retailer did not beat their estimates.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Penney dropped $1.438 to $16.50 after reporting that its
second-quarter operating profit dropped 90 percent due to lower
sales and price cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Drugmakers, which have benefitted from investors' turn toward
defensive stocks that can better withstand an economic downturn,
were mostly lower.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb, which made a legal maneuver Tuesday that
seems to temporarily preserve its patent protection on its
blockbuster cancer drug Taxol, rose $1.875 to $52.50. Generic
drugmaker Ivax, which was poised to start making a cheaper, generic
Taxol, plunged $13 to $29.375.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks of HMOs, which have soared this summer, came back to
Earth. Those included WellPoint Health Networks, off $5.187 to
$85.938 and PacifiCare Health Systems, down $2.25 to $54.25.
</P>
<P>
   Among the biggest losers in financial services, was Lehman
Brothers, off $6.625 at $130.75, and Schwab, down $2.25 at $37.75.
</P>
<P>
   Among technology stocks, JDS Uniphase fell $2.062 to $118.188
and Radio Shack dropped $2.937 to $66.063.
</P>
<P>
   But semiconductor and chip issues helped the Nasdaq, led by
Applied Materials, up $3 to $77.813 and Texas Instruments, up $3.25
to $67.
</P>
<P>
   On the economic front, the Federal Reserve said industrial
production rose 0.4 percent in July, in line with analysts'
expectations. The report contained little sign of inflation, which
should make investors more confident the central bank will leave
interest rates unchanged when it convenes next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume came to 1.09
billion shares, up from Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 4.55 to 509.93.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.89 percent,
Germany's DAX index was down 0.33 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
up 0.87 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
