<HEADLINE> US Mint Gets 105 Capitol Coin Ideas  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. Mint announced Tuesday it has
received 105 design concepts for the U.S. Capitol Visitor Center
Commemorative Coin, to be released next January.
</P>
<P>
   All the designs, including some submitted by sculptors and
engravers who work for the Mint, depict the first convening of
Congress in the Capitol in 1800.
</P>
<P>
   The designs will be reviewed by a citizen advisory committee.
The treasury secretary will select the winning design in
consultation with the U.S. Capitol Preservation Commission and the
U.S. Commission of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the revenue from sales of the dollar and half-dollar
coins will go to the new Capitol Visitor Center, which will provide
an educational experience for the 5 million or so people a year who
visit the historic building.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.usmint.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
