<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haddonfield teen pledges not to speak for a year  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   HADDONFIELD, N.J. (AP) - It started as a matter of idle
curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Banfe wondered aloud to a friend what it would be like not
to talk for a day. Then the 18-year-old said he could go a whole
year without speaking. The next thing he knew, he had committed to
do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning at 6 p.m. Sept. 1, the Haddonfield teen will stop
talking. He'll let himself make noises, but utter no words.
</P>
<P>
   Staying silent will be a big adjustment for Brett, a talkative,
friendly, outgoing kid. ''I babble,'' he said after giving a
long-winded answer to a reporter's question Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But while he's talkative, he is also contemplative. He sees the
adventure he's about to take as more about commitment than silence,
more about listening than not speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm embarrassed to say, almost, that I wouldn't listen to
people if they talked. I'd wait for them to stop talking, then I'd
start talking. Because ... my opinion was the right one anyway. It
was like, 'Thanks a lot for your input, but here's how it really
happened.' So I think the one area that I'll transform is how I
listen to people.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett also acknowledges that he's had a problem in the past
seeing things through and achieving goals.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got a 1300 on my SATs, and I failed a class. It was stupid.
And I realize why. It's because there's a difference between
wanting to get an A and being committed to getting an A,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, ''I understand commitment to the 'nth' degree. It
doesn't matter what you want. It's what you're committed to. You
have to stick to what you're committed to.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wants to use his experience to inspire people to
appreciate life.
</P>
<P>
   ''We go through our life like it's business as usual,'' said
Brett, a tall, thin, dark-haired teen with pierced ears and a
pierced tongue. ''It doesn't even occur to us that all we have is
this moment, right now, right here.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you can take a day to stop speaking, you can really get
focused and in tune with everything that's around you, all your
surroundings. If you really get in tune, it's stopping and taking
in what actually you are doing. And that's pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after he stops talking, he will start his freshman year
at William Paterson University in Wayne. He'll be able to e-mail
his family and friends at home and communicate in chat rooms, but
just how he will handle classes and new friends remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Brett and his mother, Sharon Banfe, are e-mailing his professors
this week to ''try to get a feel for how much of a problem this
will or won't be in class,'' his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some professors might be very happy to have someone who just
wants to pay attention and listen,'' she said. ''Others might
require more interaction. We don't know what's in store there.''
</P>
<P>
   For group-discussion classes, Brett said thinks he can manage by
typing on his laptop computer or writing his thoughts on paper.
</P>
<P>
   As for socializing, ''I guess I'll just make friends silently,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Web site, Dare for Dollars, has promised to pay Brett $20 for
every day he does not talk, plus a $5,000 bonus if he makes it the
whole year, for a total of more than $12,000. Brett said he'll give
the money to a charity for underprivileged inner-city kids.
</P>
<P>
   He said he knows people will try to get him to talk, but doesn't
think he'll fall for it. ''If I had a friend who wasn't speaking,
I'd try and mess him up, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett's also not worried about any physical problems from not
talking. He checked with his family doctor, who said he'll use the
same muscles chewing, coughing and grunting as he would have by
talking.
</P>
<P>
   He admits a little fear about what he's attempting. ''Sometimes
I get nervous about what I'm doing, and then I recommit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It'll be a journey that I have no idea where it'll end up. I
know that it'll be an incredible learning experience,'' he said.
''I don't know exactly what I'm going to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.notspeaking.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
