<HEADLINE> Park Avenue gynecologist asks court to let him resume medical practice </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Park Avenue gynecologist who is charged with
fraud, negligence and incompetence, has asked the court to lift the
suspension of his medical license so he can resume his
celebrity-studded practice.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Niels Lauersen, 63, said the state Health Department
violated his due process rights when it suspended his license on
Aug. 9 without a complete hearing after declaring that he posed an
''imminent danger to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed Monday in Manhattan's State Supreme Court,
Lauersen, dubbed the ''Dyno Gyno'' by tabloid newspapers, asked the
court to bar the state from acting until ongoing hearings in his
case are complete.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Phyllis Gangel-Jacob is to hear oral
arguments at 2 p.m. Wednesday on Lauersen's petition to resume his
practice. The state Attorney General's office will represent the
Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   State Health Commissioner Dr. Antonia Novello suspended Lauersen
on the basis of a report detailing numerous charges involving seven
patients, including a delivery in which a baby allegedly was brain
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Kristine Smith, spokeswoman for the Health Department, said
Lauersen's arguments for the stay ''are without merit. We have
provided compelling evidence (for the suspension) and are prepared
to proceed with our case.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith denied that Lauersen's due process rights were violated.
''He was receiving the hearing he was entitled to under the law,''
she said. ''That same law allows for summary suspension if they
(the hearing officers) feel he poses a risk to his patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the hearing officers - two doctors and a layman
knowledgeable about misconduct law - found Lauersen ''confused and
incoherent'' during the hearing and said that sometimes he seemed
to be lying.
</P>
<P>
   Lauersen's lawyer, Robert Deutsch, did not return a call for
comment. He reportedly has called the agency's charges against his
client a ''vendetta.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lauersen, whose patients have included singer Celine
Dion and actress Liv Ullman, faces retrial on federal charges that
he stole more than $2 million from insurance companies over a
10-year period by falsely billing for fertility surgeries that the
companies did not cover.
</P>
<P>
   Lauersen's first trial ended in March with a deadlocked jury.
</P>
</TEXT>
