<HEADLINE> Trans World acquires majority of used-media upstart  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Trans World Entertainment Corporation
Tuesday announced an agreement to acquire a majority interest in
Denver-based SecondSpin.com.
</P>
<P>
   SecondSpin buys and sells used CDs, videos and DVDs online as
well as at traditional marketplaces. The company now has two
locations in California and two locations in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   TransWorld's agreement - an initial $5 million investment
combined with promise of $10 million in additional financing -
amounts to a 77 percent share in SecondSpin.com's assets.
</P>
<P>
   Trans World Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Robert J.
Higgins called the move ''another step in the evolution of our
clicks and bricks strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Trans World operates 940 retail stores in 45 states, the
District of Columbia, the U.S. Virgin Islands and Puerto Rico. Its
retailers include Camelot, Record Town, The Wall, Saturday Matinee,
F.Y.E., Coconuts Music and Movies, Strawberries Music, Spec's and
Planet Music. It also has an online presence.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, traded on the NASDAQ, closed at $10.31, up 25 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
