<HEADLINE> Dutch Diplomats Visit 4 Detainees  </HEADLINE>
By KATARINA KRATOVAC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Dutch diplomats on Tuesday visited
four countrymen for the first time since their arrest on
allegations of planning to assassinate President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ''The detainees were very glad to see us, it's for the first
time in almost four weeks that they had the opportunity to talk to
someone from their own country,'' Dutch charge d'affaires, Kees
Klompenhouwer, told reporters
</P>
<P>
   ''They have been going through a very difficult time,''
Klompenhouwer said.
</P>
<P>
   The four -- Jeroen van Lersel, Bas van Schaik, Sander Zeitsen and
Godfrid de Rie -- were arrested last month on suspicion of plotting
to kill Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav authorities had not allowed Dutch diplomats to visit
their countrymen until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The four were sentenced Friday to 30 days in jail for illegally
entering the country, while remaining under investigation on other
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Klompenhouwer said that the four were allowed on Tuesday to
appoint their own attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's information minister, Goran Matic, has said that
the men were detained in July in southern Yugoslavia, attempting to
enter Kosovo province from Montenegro, Serbia's junior partner in
the two-state Yugolslav federation.
</P>
<P>
   Matic exhibited footage allegedly showing an interrogation of
the four, dressed in military uniforms, with one of them admitting
on tape to wanting to abduct Milosevic or former Bosnian Serb
leader Radovan Karadzic ''if we come across them'' and ''surrender
them to The Hague.'' Both have been indicted by the U.N. war crimes
tribunal in The Hague about atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   The video also showed maps, pocket tools, knifes and cameras
allegedly used by the Dutch. Another unidentified captive told the
camera that if the abduction of Milosevic failed, one of them ''had
the idea to kill the president, to decapitate his head, to put it
in the box and to send it home'' to the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Belgrade supreme military court completed its
investigation of two Britons and two Canadians arrested by the
Yugoslav Army on suspicion of terrorism. The military prosecutor is
expected to decide within a week whether to bring charges or drop
the case.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the arrests of foreigners follows allegations
that NATO has hired mercenaries to snatch fugitive war crimes
suspects on Yugoslav territory.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the arrests are part of a government campaign meant
to strengthen Milosevic ahead of presidential and parliamentary
elections next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
