<HEADLINE> Judge admits to confrontation but denies she shouted profanities  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - As the public trial over her private life
continued, a judge admitted to an angry confrontation with a former
boyfriend but denied shouting profanities at his female companion.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Rosemarie Williams was the final witness Tuesday, the
third day of testimony in this first-ever public disciplinary
hearing for a state Superior Court judge.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 48, is accused of posing as a police officer after a
series of public disputes she had with Alfred ''Wes'' Bridges, 27.
The judge met Bridges, a sheriff's officer, while serving at the
Mercer County courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The charges could ultimately force Williams, a judge since 1993,
off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   On April 14, Williams said she spotted Bridges entering the
Ewing Township restaurant where she and a lawyer from the public
defender's office were eating.
</P>
<P>
   Both Williams and her dining companion told the Supreme Court
Advisory Committee on Judicial Conduct Bridges' appearance made the
judge angry.
</P>
<P>
   ''I walked up to him and said 'Hello, Wes,' and he laughed. I
said, 'One of us should leave and I'm in the middle of my
dinner,''' Williams testified.
</P>
<P>
   She then followed Bridges as he headed to the men's room, she
said. Minutes later there was another confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Williams told the panel headed by retired Supreme Court
Associate Justice Alan Handler she had problems recalling exactly
what was said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were a lot of things said. It was a very, very heated
moment,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge helped Bridges get into law school and she continued
to help him with homework, she testified.
</P>
<P>
   Bridges pushed her and she grabbed at his shirt, Williams said.
Among the 25 items logged as evidence against Williams is a blue
shirt with a torn right sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   Williams claimed Bridges used her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt that he once again exploited me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the restaurant, Williams confronted Bridges and
companion Tami DeVitas of Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, DeVitas testified that Williams was ''loud and
boisterous'' and she used profane language to ask if she was having
sex with Bridges.
</P>
<P>
   The judge denied ever using foul language in public that night,
including a common vulgarity.
</P>
<P>
   ''No. I know that in our private lives we all use different
language and that is a word that is well known to me. Yes, I use
it,'' Williams said, but ''never in public.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said she drove to Trenton after Bridges left, instead
of heading to her Hopewell Township home. Bridges told her he and
the woman were going to another restaurant there, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   In Trenton she saw Bridges and DeVitas outside a popular Market
Street bar and restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   While Williams talked to her secretary on a cell phone, Bridges
approached.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard Mr. Bridges come in yelling, 'You're going to lose
your job,''' secretary Pam Fruscione testified.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said she put the telephone down and approached Bridges,
who said he planned to call police.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the restaurant, a worker called police. Others have
testified that Williams also called police in an attempt to
undercut their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   One witness told the panel that after she left the Trenton bar,
a woman called claiming to be a Hopewell Township police officer
and demanded to talk to Bridges. The state claims that was
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is likely to be the final witness. The proceeding is
scheduled to continue Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
