<HEADLINE> Oyster Creek nuclear plant shut down for repair  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FORKED RIVER, N.J. (AP) - Operators shut down the reactor at the
Oyster Creek Nuclear Generating Station on Tuesday to investigate
malfunctioning valves, said AmerGen, its new owner.
</P>
<P>
   There was no release of radiation above normal operating
conditions, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The reactor was shut down at 6:20 a.m. so operators could
investigate why two isolation valves were not working properly, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   Operators were performing a test on the system that filters and
removes radioactive materials that may be present in the reactor
building, the company said. The system is only required during an
emergency condition.
</P>
<P>
   The system was shut down so it can be repaired before the plant
is returned to operation, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   AmerGen, a joint venture between PECO Energy Co. and British
Energy Co. of Scotland, bought Oyster Creek Aug. 8 from
Morristown-based GPU Inc.
</P>
<P>
