<HEADLINE> Rash of burglaries linked to escape of burglar from Middlesex Jail  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   OLD BRIDGE, N.J. (AP) - Thomas J. Robinson, serving a 10-year
term at the Middlesex County Jail for burglaries here and awaiting
sentencing for other burglaries he committed after escaping last
year, is again at large.
</P>
<P>
   He walked away in mid-July from ''some kind of workshop'' that
he was permitted to attend during the day, police Lt. William
Volkert said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Police think about a half-dozen burglaries here since then are
no coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   ''The way the jobs are committed resembles the things he's done
in the past,'' Volkert said.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to give specifics, but said that jewelry and cash
was taken and no one was at home during the entries.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 52, should not have been given privileges, given his
prior escape, Volkert said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We locked the guy up twice, we put him away twice, and they
let him out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left late Tuesday afternoon for officials at the jail,
in North Brunswick, were not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson lived in Old Bridge, is originally from the Atlantic
Highlands area in Monmouth County, and has family in Wayne, Passaic
County, Volkert said.
</P>
</TEXT>
