<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Envoy To Seek New Mideast Talks  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the deadline for a Mideast settlement
less than a month away, top U.S. mediator Dennis Ross leaves
Wednesday to sound out Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on prospects for another summit.
</P>
<P>
   Ross will be in the region about two weeks, partly on vacation
but also trying to find out if options that were on the table at
Camp David last month can be revamped to produce an agreement, a
senior U.S. official told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is prepared to hold a second summit meeting
with Barak and Arafat if they are ready to make decisions on key
issues, including the future of Jerusalem, said the official,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The first summit collapsed primarily over Jerusalem, with Arafat
demanding sovereignty over the eastern portion of the city.
</P>
<P>
   But the official said there could be new formulations of last
month's positions that now might be acceptable. And Arafat, in a
tour of Arab capitals since the breakdown, has gained backing for
any formula he considers honorable, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, many Arab leaders take a tougher stand. President
Hosni Mubarak of Egypt has said no Arab or Muslim state could
relinquish claims to Jerusalem and holy sites in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Crown Prince Abdullah of Saudi Arabia, meanwhile, has said there
can be no peace until Israel relinquishes East Jerusalem, which was
held by Jordan from 1948 until Israeli troops reunited the city in
the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp David, Barak offered to place the Muslim and Christian
quarters of the old Walled City under Palestinian administration
along with two other Palestinian neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Arafat would have had the right to fly the Palestinian
flag on the Temple Mount, a site holy to both Jews and Muslims in
the Old City.
</P>
<P>
   According to well-placed Israeli sources, Palestinian
negotiators informed their Israeli counterparts that Arafat was
under threat of death from Arab extremists and that settling for
anything less than Palestinian control of East Jerusalem could have
cost Arafat his life.
</P>
<P>
   Barak took his proposals off the table and quit the summit over
the sovereignty issue.
</P>
<P>
   However, the idea of reshaping the structure of the city is
under consideration again, diplomatic sources said Tuesday.
Palestinians would gain some local control, with the explosive
sovereignty issue put off for future consideration.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement also would give the Palestinians a state on more
than 90 percent of the West Bank and in Gaza. And most of the
Jewish settlements in the territories would be uprooted.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat last year fixed Sept. 13 as the deadline for an
agreement. It remains a spur to an accord, but the Clinton
administration considers reaching an agreement far more important
than any deadline, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   But time could be running out. Barak is in political peril,
mostly over the concessions he is willing to make, and Arafat is
confronted with Palestinian impatience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 2024 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
