<HEADLINE> Massive Radio Merger Cleared  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators cleared the merger between
radio giants Clear Channel Communications Inc. and AMFM Inc. on
Tuesday, subject to the companies shedding 122 radio stations to
satisfy federal ownership limits and antitrust concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the businesses will create the nation's largest radio
company.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission approval comes weeks after
the Justice Department signed off on the deal, after seeking
divestitures to address competition concerns.
</P>
<P>
   To satisfy both agencies, the companies proposed to divest,
concurrently with the merger, 122 stations, in 37 areas. These
would be sold to either third-party buyers or to an insulated
trust.
</P>
<P>
   Clear Channel, based in San Antonio, agreed to buy AMFM in
October for $16.6 billion in stock. AMFM has headquarters in
Dallas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 2052 </TRAILER>
