<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many DNC Sponsors Remain the Same  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Over roast beef and fried chicken strips,
with singer Al Green providing the entertainment, the U.S. Chamber
of Commerce rented a hotel ballroom with an intricately carved
gold-leaf ceiling to honor Tennessee Rep. Harold Ford Jr. He's a
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is clearly the location where there are the most
significant policy makers gathered in one place, along with 15,000
media representatives, so the U.S. Chamber is going to be there to
get its pro-business message out,'' chamber spokesman Frank Coleman
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, dozens of corporations and trade groups, who were as
much a part of the scene in Philadelphia as the Republican
convention delegates and the red, white and blue balloons, have set
up shop 3,000 miles away to sponsor parties for the Democrats in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   They are underwriting receptions for the party's biggest donors,
sponsoring bashes for state delegations and having parties to honor
the lawmakers who sit on congressional committees that oversee
their issues.
</P>
<P>
   The practice has drawn the wrath of some Democrats who support
changing the way campaigns are financed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Can't the Democratic convention once again be a place where
grass-roots Americans can play at least an equal role with the
well-to-do and well-connected,'' said Sen. Russell Feingold of
Wisconsin, lead Democratic sponsor of legislation to overhaul
campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Business political action committees have given around $65
million to Republican candidates, much more than the $34 million
for Democrats, according to the Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, DaimlerChrysler, which held several receptions for state
delegations in Philadelphia, has a similarly busy schedule in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth, which co-sponsored a Mardi Gras party for Rep. Billy
Tauzin, R-La., in Philadelphia, co-sponsored a similar
Louisiana-themed affair for Democratic Sen. John Breaux Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ''We deal with politicians on both sides of the aisle,'' said
Bill McCloskey, a spokesman for BellSouth, which has given more
than $6 of every $10 of its PAC money to Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth was one of 18 corporate sponsors that took over Dodger
Stadium Tuesday morning to honor the Democratic members of the
House and Senate commerce committees.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the sponsors were telecommunications companies that come
under the jurisdiction of the powerful panel, including AT&AMP;T,
Worldcom, Sprint and the United States Telecom Association, which
represents phone companies. Another co-sponsor, News Corporation,
which owns the Dodgers, is awaiting Federal Communications
Commission approval of its proposed purchase of Chris-Craft
Industries Inc., the owner of eight TV stations.
</P>
<P>
   Guests got autographs from several former Dodgers, including
outfielder Lee Lacy and pitcher Roger McDowell, took batting
practice, timed their pitches on a radar gun and received bags of
goodies.
</P>
<P>
   So there should be no doubt about the benefactors, the souvenir
T-shirts included the sponsor logos. Some corporate banners also
were strung over the railings of the second deck of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The master of ceremonies was Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., the
top Democrat on the telecommunications subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Even groups absent from the festivities are making their
presence known here.
</P>
<P>
   The National Federation of Independent Business, the
small-business lobby that has given 93 percent of its PAC money to
the GOP, ran a hospitality suite at the Pennsylvania Convention
Center, opening it to fete GOP lawmakers. There are no NFIB
receptions in Los Angeles, but the organization is still running a
hospitality suite at a Santa Monica hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't look at whether the person has a 'D' or an 'R' beside
his or her name,'' spokeswoman Angela Jones said. ''We look at how
the person votes. We have a lot of people going out to L.A. who are
pro-small business.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber, which has its president, Tom Donohue, and
chief lobbyist, Lonnie Taylor, making the rounds here, generally
supports Republicans. The chamber's PAC has given the GOP $8 of
every $10 it contributes. At the recently concluded Republican
National Convention, the business lobby used two vintage train cars
and a 165-foot yacht to throw parties in honor of GOP lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, business is nurturing its relationship with conservative
and moderate Democrats, whose votes are crucial to getting its
agenda through Congress, Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''You need some Democratic votes to get anything passed,''
Coleman said. ''There is a small and apparently growing group in
the Democratic Party who have a more sympathetic understanding of
the importance of business' contribution to America's prosperity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 2056 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
