<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kennedy's Appear at DNC Convention  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE FEINSILBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- She was a child of 8 when her uncle John F.
Kennedy was nominated for president here, only 12 when he was
killed. At age 17, she experienced the awful pain of having her
father murdered while he campaigned for the Democratic nomination
for president.
</P>
<P>
   With the July 16, 1999, airplane death of a cousin, John F.
Kennedy Jr., not far from memory, Kathleen Kennedy Townsend, 49,
was one of four Kennedys to appear before the Democratic National
Convention on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Her purpose: to speak out for sharing technology with rich and
poor alike.
</P>
<P>
   Using a figure of speech that would ring true in coastal
Maryland, where she is lieutenant governor, she said:
</P>
<P>
   ''We've established America as a lighthouse of prosperity and
peace. But this didn't happen automatically and there's no
guarantee it will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   The first Kennedy to take the podium Tuesday was her brother,
Robert F. Kennedy Jr., 46, an environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with the cadence and the urgency that were his father's
hallmark, he argued that -- contrary to what he called the
Republican view -- ''good economic policy is identical to good
environmental policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, who will be the Democrats' presidential nominee,
understands that American cannot afford ''to lose touch with the
seasons and the tides and the wilderness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''And Al Gore knows that nature connects us to God as it
connects us to our communities,'' he said. ''It is the way that God
communicates with us most forcefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Kennedy, 42, and her uncle, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, 68,
also were scheduled speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's opening session heard from a fifth Kennedy, Patrick
Kennedy, 33, son of Edward and a Rhode Island congressman. He
invoked the names of Democratic heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ''In order to make this country the kind of place that lives up
to its principles of fairness and justice for all,'' Patrick
Kennedy said, ''we need to carry on the fight of John Kennedy, we
need to carry on the fight of Robert Kennedy, we need to carry on
the fight of Martin Luther King, we need to carry on the fight of
Cesar Chavez,'' the farm workers' union leader who died in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Townsend, the oldest child of the late Robert and Ethel Kennedy,
urged the country to ensure everyone shares in the benefits of
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ''While our economy offers unprecedented opportunities, to many
Americans, the Information Age is a distant blur,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must not let it be that our wealth merely affords more
powerful computers to connect us to other elites, but sever us from
the poor in our hometowns.''
</P>
<P>
   She also encouraged government to work with labor and management
''to ensure that people of all ages and incomes have the skills the
marketplace demands.'' She urged that ''the best ideas of our
universities'' be used to create jobs. And she called for
government to undergo ''revolutionary changes'' to keep pace with
business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 2101 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000815.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crocker Makes U.S. Swim Team  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Seventeen-year-old Ian Crocker completed the
improbable trip from Maine to Sydney, claiming a spot on the U.S.
Olympic swim team by winning the 100-meter butterfly Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Crocker, the first Maine-based swimmer to even qualify for the
trials, was the latest evidence of a youth movement in the men's
program. The Portland native was the eighth teen-ager to make the
Olympic team; only one male teen, Tom Malchow, went to Atlanta four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Hannan, 20, of Baltimore was ahead of the world record
pace through 50 meters before Crocker caught him at the end,
touching in 52.78 seconds. Hannan, who attends the University of
Texas, was a surprising second in 52.81.
</P>
<P>
   Hannan ranked 70th in the world last year and his only major
international experience came at the 1999 World University Games.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Atkins became the third University of Georgia swimmer to
make the women's team when she came from behind to win the 200
backstroke in 2:12.97.
</P>
<P>
   Lea Maurer, a 29-year-old high school English teacher who made
the team in 1992, led through 150 meters but apparently went out
too fast. She faded on the final lap and was passed by four other
swimmers, including Lindsay Benko of Los Angeles, who claimed the
second Olympic berth in 2:13.19.
</P>
<P>
   Maurer, of Winnetka, Ill., slipped to fifth in 2:15.12.
</P>
<P>
   Atkins, cheered on by the chant of ''It's great to be a Georgia
Bulldog,'' joined college teammates Kristy Kowal and Courtney
Shealy on the Olympic team. Together, the threesome led the Dawgs
to consecutive NCAA championships.
</P>
<P>
   A weary Dara Torres was still better than everyone else in
preliminaries of the 50 freestyle. She breezed through the
preliminaries in 25.23, putting her in the evening semifinals at
the Indiana University Natatorium.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a little bit tired,'' Torres, 33, said. ''I didn't think
it would be this tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Van Dyken, defending Olympic champion in the 50, trailed
Torres in 25.45. The top eight from the semifinals advanced to
Wednesday night's final.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do feel I can win it,'' Van Dyken said. ''This race is my
baby. It's been my baby for a long time. Dara is ahead of me right
now. But I enjoy being the underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   Torres, who came out of retirement in June 1999, was swimming
her fourth event of the eight-day trials, having finished second to
Jenny Thompson in both the 100 butterfly and 100 freestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Torres also competed in the prelims of the 200 free, but was
forced to drop out because of uterine cramping. She wonders now why
she even tried that event.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was really ridiculous,'' Torres said. ''I thought about
scratching but, no, I had to be some kind of wonder woman. I should
have taken the day off. That took a lot out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 100 free, Torres crawled from the pool with severe leg
cramps, nearly collapsing on the deck. Returning to the pool
Tuesday morning, the pre-meet advice from coach Richard Quick was
ringing true.
</P>
<P>
   ''Richard told me, 'It's a long meet. You need to know it's
going to take a lot out of you,''' Torres recalled. ''I said,
'Right, whatever.'''
</P>
<P>
   The last full day of the trials was highlighted by Gary Hall Jr.
in the men's 50 free.
</P>
<P>
   The silver medalist from the Atlanta Games eclipsed 22 seconds
in both the prelims and semis, sending him to the eight-man final
with a shot at breaking the decade-old American record of 21.81
held by Tom Jager.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, suspended for a positive marijuana test in 1998 and
diagnosed last year with diabetes, was being challenged by
defending world champion Bill Pilczuk, Neil Walker and Anthony
Ervin, who became the first swimmer of black heritage to make the
team as part of the relay team.
</P>
<P>
   Brooke Bennett of Plant City, Fla., and Diana Munz of Chagrin
Falls, Ohio, were expected to battle in the women's 800 free, the
event Bennett won at the Atlanta Games.
</P>
<P>
   The trials conclude Wednesday with the women's 50 free and the
marathon of swimming, the men's 1,500 free.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Thompson, bronze medalist at the 1999 Pan Pacific
championships, was fastest qualifier in the 1,500. The 21-year-old
from Roseburg, Ore., finished in 15:21.71 and hopes to break George
DiCarlo's 16-year-old American record of 15:01.51.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been slowly improving every year -- 10 seconds here, 20
seconds there,'' Thompson said. ''I'm not a superstar who came out
of nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson also would like to end the U.S. drought in the 1,500.
The Americans haven't won an Olympic medal since Mike O'Brien and
DiCarlo went 1-2 at the 1984 Los Angeles Games.
</P>
<P>
   ''That doesn't count because the Russians weren't there,''
Thompson said. ''The mentality of a lot of an Americans is the
quick, easy thing. They like being the fastest. They don't want to
put in the hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   The other Thompson, Jenny, dropped out of the women's 50 free
after qualifying for Sydney in at least four events. Also absent
was Angel Martino, second to Van Dyken in the 1996 trials. Martino
left this year after failing to make the 100 free final.
</P>
<P>
   ''You always want the best swimmers in there,'' Torres said,
''but you've got to do what's best for you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 2103 </TRAILER>
