<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nurses at Virtua's Mount Holly hospital approve 37-month contract  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Registered nurses employed by
Virtua/Memorial Hospital of Burlington County voted Tuesday to
approve a 37-month contract addressing some of the industry's
thorniest issues.
</P>
<P>
   The union nurses, who work at the Mount Holly hospital or for
its home care service, won a contract that boosts wages
substantially, provides bonuses for increasing their skills and
sharply limits forced overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Jeanne Otersen said about 75 percent of the 650
nurses voted. The contract was approved by 98.5 percent of those
who voted, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The nurses' union, the Emerson-based Health Professionals and
Allied Employees, recommended approval of the contract after
reaching an agreement Monday, according to Otersen. The deal offers
an average wage increase of 14 percent over its three years.
</P>
<P>
   It also limits mandatory overtime - a serious problem for the
many nurses with children - to two extra four-hour shifts each
month, and only when an emergency exists. Nurses at many hospitals
complain that tight staffing routinely forces them to work long
hours when co-workers are ill.
</P>
<P>
   Under the contract, the nurses must get an hour's notice before
any overtime begins, plus time to arrange child care or to pick up
and drop their children off with a babysitter, if needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Management at Virtua/Memorial really listened to the
experiences of nurses and our concerns over staffing, overtime, and
recruitment and retention of qualified nurses,'' said Joan Johnson,
president of the HPAE local at the hospital. ''This contract
reflects the commitment of both the RNs and the hospital to nursing
excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract runs from Aug. 27, when the current one expires,
until Sept. 27, 2003. It includes provisions to give bonuses for
continuing education or earning new certifications, and gives
cumulative raises as big as 25 percent to the most experienced
hospital nurses and those in the hospital's Community Nursing
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ''Patients are leaving the hospital more quickly, meaning that
their needs for home care have increased dramatically,'' said Patty
Nelson, who handles grievances for nurses in the home care service.
''With this contract, we can attract and keep skilled nurses in
home care.''
</P>
<P>
   Nurses and union activists say limited salary increases,
staffing shortages and increased patient loads have been driving
experienced nurses out of the business, contributing to the growing
national shortage of nurses and threatening the quality of patient
care.
</P>
<P>
   Even executives at New Jersey hospitals - most of which are
losing money because of slashed reimbursements from the government
and insurers - seem to accept the view that contracts addressing
such concerns are key to retaining good nurses.
</P>
<P>
   ''A big part of Virtua's present and future is in nursing
excellence, and certainly this type of contract creates that type
of partnership with our nurses,'' said Ed Dunn, vice president of
human resources for Virtua Health, which operates the Mount Holly
hospital and others in Berlin, Camden, Marlton and Voorhees.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe it's a fair contract for the nurses, for the
organization, and it will help us serve the community,'' Dunn said
Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Contracts recently negotiated at Robert Wood Johnson University
Hospital in New Brunswick and Cooper Hospital/University Medical
Center in Camden included provisions limiting forced overtime and
floating of nurses to unfamiliar units.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, HPAE, other nursing unions and the statewide Patients
First Coalition have been urging Gov. Whitman to sign legislation
limiting the use of mandatory overtime in hospitals and nursing
homes. The legislation, sponsored by Sen. Joseph Vitale and
Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, was passed and sent to the governor
in late June.
</P>
<P>
   ''HPAE and Virtua/Burlington are ahead of the curve,'' said
Vitale. ''I congratulate them, and hope their achievements can be
duplicated statewide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-15-00 2103 </TRAILER>
