<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, Aug. 15, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russia Lowers Capsule To Sunken Sub
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian rescuers lowered a bell-shaped capsule early Wednesday
to a nuclear submarine lying on the Arctic Sea floor, but there was no immediate
word that it had docked. Oxygen for the vessel's 116 crewmen was expected last
just two more days, Russia's navy chief said. It was the first word that the
escape apparatus had reached the vicinity of the sunken submarine -- which U.S.
officials said might have gone down following an explosion -- since repeated
efforts that began Tuesday were foiled by storms on the Barents Sea.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kennedys Appear at DNC Convention
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kathleen Kennedy Townsend, 49, was one of four Kennedys
featured tonight before the Democratic National Convention. Townsend, the
lieutenant governor of Maryland, spoke out for sharing technology with rich and
poor alike. Before that, her brother, Robert F. Kennedy Jr., an
environmentalist, urged Democrats to back Al Gore. Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg,
the daughter of President Kennedy, and her uncle, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, his
brother, also were to speak.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Passes Leadership To Gore
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONROE, Mich. (AP) -- Al Gore stepped out of President Clinton's bear hug and
claimed front stage in the Midwest today, a grateful understudy, ''partner and
friend'' promising not to let Republicans undo what Clinton had built for the
nation. ''We're going forward, to even better times,'' the vice president
declared to a cheering crowd after Clinton left the lectern that bore his
presidential seal. ''Bill Clinton worked hard to get this economy right. And I'm
pledging to you here today, I am not going to let the other side wreck it and
take it away from us.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lieberman Favors Affirmitive Action
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Democratic vice presidential candidate Joseph Lieberman
allayed the concerns of some prominent blacks -- an important Democratic
constituency -- by telling them today he would stand with them in support of
affirmative action and civil rights. Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., who had been
the most vocal in expressing doubts about Lieberman, said afterward that she
would campaign for him. The senator from Connecticut reminded about 300 members
of the Congressional Black Caucus, the Democratic National Committee's Black
Caucus and others that in 1963, he marched on Washington with Martin Luther King
Jr. and went into Mississippi to register black voters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. To Seek New Mideast Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the deadline for a Mideast peace settlement less than
a month away, top U.S. mediator Dennis Ross leaves tomorrow to sound out Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat on prospects for
another summit. Ross will be trying to find out if options that were on the
table at Camp David last month can be revamped to produce an agreement, a senior
U.S. official told The Associated Press. President Clinton is prepared to hold a
second summit meeting with Barak and Arafat if they are ready to make decisions
on key issues, including the future of Jerusalem, said the official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
British Airways Suspends Concordes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Warned of new official doubts about the Concorde's tires,
British Airways grounded its supersonic fleet, even pulling a New York-bound
plane off the runway. The airline was told that British and French officials
looking into last month's Air France Concorde disaster intended to revoke the
jet's airworthiness certification. Later, the French Transport Ministry said the
safety concerns focused on the plane's tires and that a formal recommendation
that all Concorde flights be suspended was imminent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Compaq and Microsoft Launch 'Appliance'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Two stalwarts of the PC, Compaq Computer Corp. and Microsoft
Corp., joined together today to launch a simple, stripped-down ''Internet
appliance'' they hope will woo those who find PCs daunting. Such devices are
expected to become a major way to get online in the future, but Microsoft
executive Rick Belluzzo said they would be complements to, not replacements for,
the PC.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 109; Nasdaq Is Up 2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks finished mixed today, as investors sold blue chips
after three straight winning sessions and bought some beaten down technology
issues. The Dow Jones industrial average ended down 109.14 at 11,067.00,
according to preliminary calculations. On the NYSE, losers led gainers by
3-to-2. The Nasdaq composite index was up 1.97 at 3,851.66.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mets 7, Rockies 5, 1st Game
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Todd Helton went 2-for-4 to inch closer to .400, but control
problems did in the Colorado Rockies as they lost the opener of a doubleheader
7-5 to the New York Mets tonight. The Rockies walked eight batters -- including
two with the bases loaded in the seventh inning -- as the Mets broke a 4-4 tie
on a run-scoring wild pitch to win for the 17th time in 21 games.
AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER 
</P>
