<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jazz Rookie Charged With Misdemeanor  </HEADLINE>
By BRIAN MELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- Utah Jazz rookie DeShawn Stevenson was
charged with a misdemeanor Tuesday for throwing punches in a high
school brawl on the night he was drafted.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson, 19, and Fresno State football recruit Christopher Lee
Sims, 18, were charged with fighting in a public place, according
to a complaint by the Fresno County District Attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Sims also was charged with misdemeanor counts of resisting
arrest and possessing a deadly weapon, a razor knife, on school
property.
</P>
<P>
   The fight broke out June 28 after Stevenson, who was selected in
the first round by Utah, attended a high school all-star basketball
game as a spectator and signed autographs at Buchanan High School
in nearby Clovis.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess there were some dudes there who didn't like me,''
Stevenson said later. ''I got done signing autographs and five guys
jumped me.''
</P>
<P>
   As many as 20 people were involved in the melee, and Sims and
another man were arrested. Stevenson was listed as a suspect in
police reports but was not charged until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Richard Berman said Stevenson was attacked by two
men on what should have been the greatest day in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ''DeShawn is an innocent man,'' Berman said. ''He's someone
Fresno can be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   No charges were filed Tuesday against Calvin John Howell, 20,
the other man arrested for fighting and disturbing the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson was practicing in the area Tuesday, but has kept a low
profile since the incident and has refused to comment on the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Sims, who played in the all-star game, told police that
Stevenson and his friends started the fight. He did not immediately
return calls for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In results of a lie-detector test that Berman said vindicates
his client, Stevenson said Sims charged him and threw the first
punch. He said he only returned blows in self-defense as he
retreated.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses told investigators the fight was spurred by jealousy
over a woman both men had dated, a police report said.
</P>
<P>
   An arraignment was scheduled Monday in Fresno Superior Court,
but Berman said he would appear in court for his client as early as
Wednesday. Berman does not expect Stevenson to appear in court in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, the maximum penalty for fighting is 90 days in
jail and a $400 fine. The additional charges Sims faces carry up to
a year in prison each and a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson, a 6-foot-5 guard who averaged 30.4 points, 9.7
rebounds and 6.2 assists as a senior last season at Washington
Union High School in Easton, was the 23rd overall pick in the NBA
draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz said it was standing by Stevenson and the fight
wouldn't affect his role with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see DeShawn entirely as the victim so we support him,''
said Jazz spokesman David Allred.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson originally committed to play college basketball at
Kansas, but entered the NBA draft in May when his SAT score was
questioned after a dramatic improvement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 2127 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000815.0156 </DOCNO>
