<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Celebrities Talk About Arts, Music  </HEADLINE>
By CHELSEA J. CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Talk about music and arts education and
celebrities will listen.
</P>
<P>
   Actors Christopher Reeve and Hector Elizondo, star of the TV
hospital drama ''Chicago Hope,'' headlined a celebrity-studded
panel Tuesday that discussed the benefits of it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope this doesn't fall on deaf ears,'' Elizondo said.
</P>
<P>
   But it might just have since the panel -- sponsored by the
Creative Coalition and VH1's ''Save the Music'' -- was preaching to
the choir. The audience included comedian Tom Arnold, actors Peter
Boyle of ''Everybody Loves Raymond'' and Cary Elwes of ''The
Princess Bride'' and film producer Lawrence Bender. Screenwriter
Steve Sunshine also attended.
</P>
<P>
   What was really needed, according to Creative Coalition
president William Baldwin, was a televised panel.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it's televised we could get the message out across the
country instead of to a room of 250 people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeve said studies show that music and arts education helps
students perform better in school and work environments.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we have to do is convince these (politicians) that music
and arts education ... is good for the economy,'' Reeve said. ''The
Republicans are reasonable people. They just need to know what the
benefits are.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Mixing politics with music, two of Al Gore's daughters visited
the legendary House of Blues on Tuesday and announced their father
will do an MTV town hall meeting next month.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm here to tell you that my father is extremely tuned into
the issues facing this generation,'' Kristin Gore told about 700
young people attending MTV's ''Choose or Lose 2000'' party
featuring R&AMP;B singer Kina Cosper.
</P>
<P>
   Kina performed her latest single, ''Girl from the Gutter,'' from
her self-titled album, as well as an upcoming single, ''Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before taking the stage, the gold and glitter-bedecked
Kina said she didn't consider herself political until very
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel a need to get involved,'' said the singer, explaining
that there were many issues facing the black community that have to
be addressed, from poverty to health care.
</P>
<P>
   Kristin Gore and sister Karenna Gore Schiff told the crowd their
father would appear for an MTV town hall meeting on Sept. 26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 2134 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000815.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman: Faith May Halt Campaign  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Vice presidential candidate Joseph Lieberman
said Tuesday that his devotion to Orthodox Judaism would keep him
off the campaign trail on several crucial days before the election.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just going to do what I've always done and work extra hard
on the days that I'm campaigning,'' Lieberman said in an interview
with The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman last week was chosen as Al Gore's Democratic running
mate, the first Jew ever selected for a major party national
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Rosh Hashanah, the Jewish New Year, falls on Sept. 30 and Oct.
1. Yom Kippur, the day of atonement, falls on Oct. 9. Sukkot, the
Jewish harvest festival, arrives Oct. 14 and 15. Simchat Torah, an
annual celebration of finishing reading the Torah -- the word of God
-- and beginning again comes on Oct. 22. Election Day is Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ''Al Gore is a man of faith and he respects my faith and my
observance and he's been very clear that he doesn't want me to vary
from my traditional practices and I won't,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman suggested that his faith won't sway him from defending
U.S. interests over Israel concerns, if it came to that.
</P>
<P>
   ''In Middle East matters, in most cases over time, American
policy has been quite similar to Israeli policy. But if they ever
diverge, as they have occasionally, my record shows that I've
supported obviously the U.S. position,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   He cited as an example a plan by Israel to sell a
quarter-billion-dollar advanced airborne radar warning system to
China. The Clinton administration opposed it and so did Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   ''My first and only loyalty is to the United States of
America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish holidays fall mostly on Saturdays and Sundays.
Lieberman also observes the Jewish Sabbath, the traditional day for
worship and rest that stretches from sundown Friday to sundown
Saturday. On the Sabbath, Jews are prohibited from working, driving
operating mechanical devices or even using electricity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 2140 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000815.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Jumps Off S. Francisco Bridge  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The boyfriend of a woman whose body was
found along a remote coastal highway killed himself Tuesday by
jumping off the Bay Bridge, shortly after the body was identified,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   Darion Sable jumped off an approach to the San Francisco-Oakland
Bay Bridge Tuesday afternoon, police spokesman Dewayne Tully said.
He fell about 100 feet, landing on pavement in a fenced-in area.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes earlier and five blocks away, Sable had been
released on his own recognizance after being jailed overnight on a
drug charge, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Homicide Inspector Tony Casillas wouldn't say whether police
told Sable he was a suspect in his girlfriend's death before
letting him go.
</P>
<P>
   ''The investigation is still in its primary stages,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sable told police that Jerusha Briley, 20, disappeared Saturday
morning while going to buy groceries for her 23-month-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Sable called police Saturday to report Briley missing, saying
she wasn't the type to leave the house, let alone her toddler, for
more than a few hours without letting people know where she was.
</P>
<P>
   Briley's body was found Monday. Police haven't determined the
cause of death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 2146 </TRAILER>
