<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman Favors Affirmitive Action  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Democratic vice presidential candidate Joseph
Lieberman allayed the concerns of some prominent blacks -- an
important Democratic constituency -- by telling them Tuesday he
would stand with them in support of affirmative action and civil
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., who had been the most vocal in
expressing doubts about Lieberman, said afterward that she would
campaign for him.
</P>
<P>
   The senator from Connecticut reminded about 300 members of the
Congressional Black Caucus, the Democratic National Committee's
Black Caucus and others that in 1963, he marched on Washington with
Martin Luther King Jr. and went into Mississippi to register black
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to say a word to you particularly about the rapport
that I have felt over my life with the African American community
in my commitment to civil rights,'' said Lieberman, an Orthodox
Jew. ''It honestly begins with my religion because I believe as a
matter of faith, not just that God created all of us, ... I believe
that every human being is created in God's image.''
</P>
<P>
   Waters, who was concerned about Lieberman's stances on
affirmative action and school vouchers, earlier had threatened to
''do nothing'' -- neither campaign nor speak -- on behalf of the
ticket led by Al Gore unless Lieberman addressed her concerns.
After meeting privately with Lieberman on Tuesday, she told
reporters she was behind the team.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has said enough, he has done enough and he has demonstrated
his willingness to deal with issues of concern to the black
community,'' Waters said. ''I feel comfortable in campaigning for
him. I was not going to do it and lose credibility if these issues
had not been clarified.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic convention speakers' podium, meanwhile,
Lieberman got the backing of civil rights leader Jesse Jackson, who
applauded Gore for placing Lieberman on the Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Jackson said, ''Al Gore has brought the sons and
daughters of slaves and slavemasters together with the sons and
daughters of Holocaust survivors.''
</P>
<P>
   A short time afterward, Lieberman swept through the convention
hall, where he was greeted by throngs of delegates who rose to
their feet, gave him high-fives and called out, ''Joe! Joe! Joe!''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's embrace of affirmative action comes after years of
skepticism about such programs as well as his continuing opposition
to what he regards as racial quotas.
</P>
<P>
   Not all prominent blacks were completely sold, however.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's selection makes it harder to energize blacks to go
the polls, said Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., the House Judiciary
Committee's top Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lieberman has to indicate he's going to be a positive part of
the team in the Gore administration and we're not going to have to
be attacking him,'' Conyers said, adding that blacks, among
themselves, ''say things we never say to the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman started the day by surveying the podium in the Staples
Center where he will give his acceptance speech Wednesday night.
Gazing at the expansive arena with a look of awe, he called it an
''only-in-America moment.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm thankful for the chance of a lifetime that Al Gore has
given me and I want to make it work,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Lieberman and Waters became friendly during their
private talk. At the beginning of his remarks, he disclosed that it
was Waters' birthday and led the crowd in singing ''Happy
Birthday.'' She is 62. After his speech, the two hugged.
</P>
<P>
   In his 20-minute speech to the audience, Lieberman acknowledged
the doubts about his voting record but said they were unfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have supported affirmative action. I do support affirmative
action. And I will support affirmative action,'' he said to
applause.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has criticized efforts to roll back affirmative action
programs aimed at helping blacks gain entrance into schools and
jobs where they've historically been underrepresented.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also sought to reassure black leaders about his
support for Proposition 209, a 1996 California proposition that
banned state-funded affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   He said that in the mid-1990s, a reporter had read the
proposition to him and that he responded favorably, saying it
sounded like a basic human rights policy.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, he never campaigned for it even though he was
asked to do so. He added that he made crucial votes in the Senate
in favor of affirmative action in 1995 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding school vouchers, Lieberman said he has only wanted to
test such a system and that his vote in favor of that test did not
draw money away from public schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-15-00 2159 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000815.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 45 DNC Protesters Arrested  </HEADLINE>
By ANTHONY BREZNICAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Animal rights activists opposed to the fur
trade protested in front of clothing stores and banged on windows
Tuesday as demonstrations continued outside the Democratic National
Convention. Police arrested about 45 people.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds also marched in support of women's rights, labor
unions, education and other causes in spirited but largely peaceful
protests one day after violent clashes with police.
</P>
<P>
   Groups orchestrated everything from their messages to their
outfits. Teachers wore red; labor wore green. Impromptu rallies
sprang up around the well-planned protests and quickly died. Small
groups of people often taunted the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Police, including some in riot gear, met the animal rights
activists about eight blocks from the Staples Center, where the
convention is being held. They also kept the public and the media
out of a two-block area around a California Federal bank while they
made arrests.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 people gathered on the periphery, clapping, banging
drums and shouting for the streets to be re-opened before police
ordered them to disperse.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were peaceful demonstrators. It was a lawful assembly. This
is an unlawful arrest,'' Geoff Kerns said as he and others were
handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   At Edward Borovay Furs, where protesters banged on the windows,
workers spray painted over the business's name on a green awning
within 90 minutes and prepared to take down a larger sign.
</P>
<P>
   Those arrested were charged with conspiracy to commit a felony
based on items found in their backpacks, including flammable
liquids and small fireworks, said Cmdr. David Kalish, a police
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In other protests, demonstrators carrying dove puppets made of
shredded white cloth marched from the abandoned $170 million
Belmont Learning Center to the nearby office of California Gov.
Gray Davis. Some chanted, ''Schools not jails!''
</P>
<P>
   Belmont, built in one of the city's poorer neighborhoods near
downtown, has become a symbol of failure for the nation's
second-largest school system. The district stopped work on the
school after learning it was being built on contaminated land.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a separate demonstration in support of unions and
women's rights moved from Pershing Square -- a center of protest
activity at the convention -- to the Roybal Federal Building, where
two lines of U.S. marshals and police in riot helmets blocked them
from entering.
</P>
<P>
   ''LAPD, go away! Racist, sexist, anti-gay!'' a crowd of hundreds
chanted.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening about 1,500 Service Employees International Union
members, marching to another downtown hall for a strike vote,
stopped for a brief rally in the protest area.
</P>
<P>
   And separately, about 1,000 people rallied against U.S. support
for sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the standoffs and arrests, Tuesday's protests were
without violence.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier outside the Staples Center, hundreds of
demonstrators threw rocks and fired steel balls from slingshots at
police, who answered by firing rubber bullets and beanbags from
shotguns, swinging batons from horseback and unleashing pepper
spray.
</P>
<P>
   The clash Monday night after a free concert by the
anti-authoritarian band Rage Against the Machine came as President
Clinton addressed the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Six people were arrested and at least four were slightly injured
as police chased the crowd, as large as 8,000 at one point, from a
fenced protest.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates inside the arena were generally unaware of the trouble
outside, and debris left from the clash -- rocks, smashed plastic
water bottles and sticks -- was removed quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Police Department, which had kept a high profile
on downtown streets throughout the day, defended its actions and
promised an equally strong response to any further trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, state Sen. Tom Hayden, a veteran of
protests at the 1968 Democratic convention in Chicago, and the
American Civil Liberties Union of Southern California accused
police of unnecessary brutality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
