<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Broward woman, 83, survives 3 days in crashed car  </HEADLINE>
By TERRY SPENCER
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) - For three days 83-year-old Tillie
Tooter survived.
</P>
<P>
   First, a thicket of mangrove and willow trees cushioned her fall
when her Toyota Tercel plummeted 40 feet off an Interstate 595
bridge after being struck from behind by a hit-and-run driver.
</P>
<P>
   The trees then kept her car suspended inches above a snake- and
alligator-infested swamp, saving Tooter from the reptiles and from
possibly drowning.
</P>
<P>
   Tooter stuck an aluminum steering wheel cover outside her broken
windshield to collect rainwater from several storms. That prevented
her from dying of thirst in the 100 degree heat.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday morning, dehydrated and covered with insect bites,
she began to lose hope, and wrote a farewell letter to her family.
</P>
<P>
   At about that moment, 15-year-old Justin Vannelli was collecting
trash on the bridge - his father's company has a state contract to
cleanup road debris. He was collecting a bumper when he noticed
some of the trees below were mangled. He looked down and saw
Tooter's car.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Fort Lauderdale Fire and Rescue firefighters were
rappelling from the bridge. Just over an hour later, Tooter was at
Broward General Medical Center, where she is expected to recover.
She was listed in serious condition late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This 83-year-old lady had it all together,'' Fire-Rescue
Division Chief Stephen McInerny said. ''That may have made a
difference between surviving and dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Tooter's ordeal began with a late airline flight.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 a.m. Saturday morning, a Continental Airlines plane
carrying Tooter's granddaughter, Lori Simms, and Simms' boyfriend,
Steven Poulos, arrived at Fort Lauderdale/Hollywood International
Airport, 3&AMP;frac12; hours late from Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Simms, a Marlboro, N.J., resident, called her grandmother to say
they would rent a car or catch a cab and head to her Pembroke Pines
condominium, about 10 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ''She said 'Don't be silly. I'm awake. I'll come get you,'''
Simms said. Despite her age, Tooter is mentally sharp and
frequently plays cards into the wee hours, Simms said. Putting
aside her misgivings, she agreed to wait for her grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Tooter never arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Worried, Simms and Poulos rented a car and drove to her condo.
Tooter wasn't there. They called the police.
</P>
<P>
   A condominium surveillance tape showed Tooter leaving the
complex at 2:54 a.m. Saturday, but now no one knew where she was.
</P>
<P>
   For three days, Pembroke Pines police officers, assisted by
other law enforcement agencies, drove the highways to the airport
and checked the nearby lakes and canals. They found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Simms, Poulos or others, who also searched the area.
Frustrated, the family called a psychic.
</P>
<P>
   ''She didn't know if (Tooter) was dead or alive, but said she
was by a tree or under a fluffy tree, right near a lake,'' Simms
said.
</P>
<P>
   The psychic, by skill or luck, was almost right.
</P>
<P>
   Tooter was stuck inside her car, which was stuck in the trees in
a swamp. She was just one mile west of the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. John Bagnardi, a spokesman for the Florida Highway Patrol,
said investigators believe Tooter's car was struck from behind by a
car or truck that did not stop.
</P>
<P>
   The force propelled Tooter's Toyota up a three-foot concrete
barrier, where it slid along the top for 60 feet before tumbling
straight down into the trees.
</P>
<P>
   The car stopped on its side, the driver's door facing down.
Tooter unbuckled her seat belt and made herself as comfortable as
possible. Somehow, she suffered no broken bones or internal
injuries, just numerous cuts and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   Tooter told her relatives that her thoughts weren't mostly about
herself, but her family and how they were coping.
</P>
<P>
   ''She is a very strong woman,'' Simms said.
</P>
<P>
   But by Tuesday morning, that strength was waning and she penned
her family a note.
</P>
<P>
   They won't say what it said, saying that's personal.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes after she penned the note, a Fort Lauderdale
Fire-Rescue team arrived. They used chain saws to clear away trees,
cut the top from her car with hydraulic tools and hooked Tooter up
to IVs.
</P>
<P>
   On the bridge, another 18 firefighters hoisted her to safety.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Moshe Stav, who treated Tooter in the emergency room, said
her lack of traumatic injuries in the initial collision allowed
Tooter to survive. But there was also something else.
</P>
<P>
   ''She had to have the will to fight,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
