<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court upholds lighter sentence for anti-nuke protesters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DENVER (AP) - A federal appeals court on Tuesday upheld lighter
sentences than the government sought for two anti-nuclear
protesters who broke into a missile silo and did $21,000 in damage.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
issued the ruling in the case of Daniel Harris Sicken of
Brattleboro, Vt., and Oliver Sachio Coe, also known as Oliver
Hydon, of Ridgewood, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The two, members of the group Plowshares Movement, waited at the
missile silo in Weld County for authorities to arrest them on Aug
6, 1998. They said they were marking the 53rd anniversary of the
atomic bombing of Hiroshima, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   A federal jury in Denver convicted the two of conspiracy to
destroy national defense materials, sabotage and destruction of
U.S. property.
</P>
<P>
   Sicken was sentenced to 41 months in prison and Coe got 30
months. They were also sentenced to three years of supervised
probation and were ordered to pay $21,299 in restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors appealed the sentences, arguing federal
guidelines called for Sicken to get up to 71 months, and Coe up to
57 months.
</P>
<P>
   The trial judge said the sentencing guidelines did not take into
consideration the seriousness of the offense and said there was a
clear difference between ''an act of protest, which this clearly
was, in peacetime as opposed to an act of sabotage during war.''
</P>
<P>
   Sicken and Coe broke into an unmanned silo containing a
Minutemen III intercontinental ballistic missile, according to
court records. They said during their trial they were protesting
nuclear weapons by ''disarming nonviolently and symbolically.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the two cut barbed wire around the silo, used
sledgehammers and chisels to damage an electrical box, the concrete
door to the silo and the rails on which the door moved.
</P>
<P>
   Sicken and Coe also poured water into a circuit and security
pit, hung banners and used spray paint mixed with blood to paint
slogans and designs.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said the lack of adjustment in the sentencing
guidelines for the crime's seriousness was a valid reason for not
following them.
</P>
<P>
   The court didn't agree with basing the lighter sentences on the
fact that it was peacetime. But the judges upheld the sentences
because the trial court also considered the risk of death or injury
and threat to national security.
</P>
<P>
   The detailed analysis ''indicated that the court gave greater
weight to these factors than to the impermissible peacetime
factor,'' the judges wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-15-00 2212 </TRAILER>
