<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Survivors Recall Sub Ordeal  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY R. WEBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- When Dan Persico heard that a Russian
submarine manned by more than 100 sailors had sunk in the Barents
Sea, his thoughts flashed back more than six decades, to when he
endured a similar ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ''It brought back instant, unpleasant memories,'' said Persico,
now 82, of Amsterdam, N.Y., one of the survivors from the USS
Squalus, which went down 13 miles off the New Hampshire coast in
1939.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the 33 survivors of the Squalus tragedy are still alive.
Twenty-six crewmen died when the sub sank in about 240 feet of
water during its trial run.
</P>
<P>
   Persico and several of the other survivors held out little hope
Monday for the trapped Russian sailors.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say these boys are in some real trouble,'' said Gerald
McLees, 85, of Portsmouth, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The drama of the Russian sub also kindled memories for another
former submarine crewman. Kimo Ward, a retired sonar technician,
helped search for a pair of U.S. nuclear subs lost at sea -- the
Thresher in 1963 and the Scorpion in 1968. No one survived either
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, from Montville, Conn., served aboard the Thresher until
1962 and was scheduled to be on the sub during its last voyage in
April 1963 -- but had been delayed. He knew half the men on the
doomed sub.
</P>
<P>
   ''You wake up and 60 of my shipmates that I had been with for
two years, all of a sudden they were gone,'' he said. All 129 men
aboard perished.
</P>
<P>
   The Squalus sank when water inlet valves opened without tripping
alarms in the control room. Investigators later blamed a mechanical
malfunction.
</P>
<P>
   The crew waited 23 hours before a Navy tugboat arrived carrying
a nine-ton diving bell. The bell was lowered to a hatch on the
Squalus to rescue the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   McLees was one of the first to ride up; Persico and Allen
Bryson, then a 21-year-old machinist's mate second class, were in
the last group. The other remaining living survivors are Carlton
Powell of Lompoc, Calif.; Carol Nathan Pierce of Louisville, Ky.;
and Warren Smith of Livingston, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''During the initial hustle and bustle of activity, you don't
have time to think, you have to stop the water from coming in,''
recalled Bryson, 82, of New London, Conn. ''Then you have to worry
about air.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't have enough,'' Bryson said. ''We had very little
oxygen.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We were given orders to lay down and take it easy on the
oxygen,'' added McLees, then a 25-year-old chief electrician's
mate.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of oxygen was not the only menace they faced on the
Squalus.
</P>
<P>
   Water had shorted out one of the ship's two batteries, creating
a rapid voltage drain. One crew member wedged himself into a narrow
crawl space to shut off the power.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's probably a little colder out there (in the Barents Sea)
than what we had, but we had no lights,'' McLees said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite growing doubt that the Russians can be rescued, Persico,
a seaman first class aboard the Squalus, offered reason for
optimism. Despite being one of the last seaman rescued, ''I never
gave up hope,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''All submariners are like a brotherhood,'' said Ward. ''We're a
very small group. Even though we were enemies at one point, we all
share something most people don't.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Submarine Memorials:
http://www.1000islands.com/(tilde)cny/history/all.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
