<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-15 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials start cleanup efforts in northwestern New Jersey  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKETTSTOWN, N.J. (AP) - Emergency officials nervously eyed
water levels at several rivers and dams Tuesday as residents
cleaned up from drenching rains that damaged thousands of homes,
wiped out dozens of bridges, roads and dams, and forced hundreds of
people to flee rising waters.
</P>
<P>
   The downpours Saturday and Monday caused many rivers and lakes
in northwestern New Jersey to rise far above normal, and
temporarily devoured Newton's water supply system.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman said she would ask the Clinton
administration to declare Morris and Sussex counties disaster
areas. She put both counties under a state of emergency, allowing
the state to order evacuations and activate New Jersey National
Guard units to help residents.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Warren County also were inundated.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Senator Robert Torricelli on Tuesday asked Clinton to
support the governor's request.
</P>
<P>
   The damage cost will surpass $100 million, Whitman spokesman
Peter McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said a kayaker who went onto the Musconetcong River,
which is swollen due to the heavy rains, Tuesday afternoon is
missing. Crews were searching for the man on the river between
Holland Township, Hunterdon County and Pohatcong, Warren County,
according to the Hunterdon County dispatch center. An official said
the area being searched is near where the Musconetcong goes into
the Delaware River.
</P>
<P>
   The search for the kayaker was called off at about 8 p.m.
Tuesday and is scheduled to resume about 10 a.m. Wednesday,
officials said. The Express-Times of Easton reported for
Wednesday's edition that the missing man is Charles Weaver, 48, of
Riegelsville.
</P>
<P>
   An early estimate of flood-related damage in Morris County was
about $12 million, said Rick Loock, county deputy emergency
management coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Sussex County officials did not release estimates Tuesday. Phil
Morlock, the county's health and public safety administrator, said
earlier that the storm caused about $166 million worth of damage -
$80 million of which was to bridges and roads.
</P>
<P>
   State Office of Emergency Management officials said damage
assessments of homes, business, roads, bridges and dams in Sussex
County were complete Tuesday afternoon, but estimates were not
immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   Warren County officials said there was no structural damage
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas such as Jefferson Township were still under water and
damage could not be assessed.
</P>
<P>
   State Police spokesman John Hagerty said 2,700 residences and
businesses in Sussex and Morris counties reported flood-related
damage.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service in Mount Holly said Tuesday morning
that there is a possibility of a quarter-inch of rain Tuesday night
into Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It'll be pretty much dry Wednesday and Thursday,''
meteorologist Dean Iovino said. ''Whatever falls (Tuesday night)
shouldn't create a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the floodwater subsided Tuesday in the hardest hit areas
of Sparta in Sussex County and Jefferson Township in Morris County.
</P>
<P>
   Eskil ''Skip'' Danielson, Sussex County's emergency coordinator,
said Byram and Stanhope still have floodwaters running through
streets, and Lake Hopatcong is still 20 inches above the spillway.
</P>
<P>
   Hagerty said the Musconetcong, which flows out of Sussex County
and borders Morris and Warren counties, remained the biggest
concern Tuesday because its water level has not receded yet.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're watching that with a cautious eye,'' Hagerty said.
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred homes in Byram and Sparta remain evacuated Tuesday
afternoon after Monday's precautionary evacuations, said Sergeant
Rick McDonnell.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents spent Monday night at a shelter at the Helen
Morgan school in Byram, said Red Cross spokeswoman Cathy
Derechailo. The shelter is scheduled to remain open Tuesday night,
Derechailo said. The other five shelters were closed.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 homes in Sussex County were evacuated since
Saturday, McDonnell said. And 500 residents were evacuated at some
point, Danielson said.
</P>
<P>
   About 51 homes in Sparta suffered some flood damage, township
manager Henry Underhill said Tuesday. At least three of the homes
are probably a total loss, he said.
</P>
<P>
   State emergency workers said 11 bridges in Sussex County
remained closed Tuesday due to water damage, flooding and erosion.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't foresee any quick fixes,'' McDonnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Three bridges and parts of three roads were swept away in
Sparta, where Main Street residents were evacuated Sunday because
fire officials feared a mudslide.
</P>
<P>
   Newton's water supply was restored late Monday night by
connecting its pipeline with Sparta's line, Danielson said. Another
water line was scheduled to be added Tuesday afternoon, but
Danielson said residents should still boil water for drinking and
cooking as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   In Morris County, up to 1,000 single family homes and 200
businesses suffered some flood-related damage, Loock said Tuesday.
He said 400 people were asked to evacuate their homes over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Five roads remained closed in one of the hardest hit area of
Jefferson Township, Loock said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything seems to be holding.'' he said. ''We're keeping our
fingers crossed with the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   Emergency workers were grateful that an additional downpour
Monday night did not add to the problem because it only lasted
about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it had continued, it probably would have given us some
problems,'' Danielson said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of northern New Jersey was hit with a half-inch to an inch
of rain Monday, according to the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen people were evacuated in Hackettstown Monday amid
concern that upstream dams could burst, according to Gary Wassel,
deputy coordinator of emergency management in Warren County.
</P>
<P>
   Derechailo said the Hackettstown residents were back in their
homes Monday night after being sheltered at Hackettstown High
School.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once they get the word they can go back, they run out of
there,'' she said. ''It's not The Ritz.''
</P>
<P>
   The Musconetcong River rose a foot an hour Monday before
cresting in mid-afternoon, Derechailo said.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few Warren County residents who lived along the
Musconetcong River were evacuated Monday, said Patrick Rivoli,
county emergency management coordinator. He said damage was limited
to flood water in basements and back yards.
</P>
<P>
   ''We fared very well,'' Rivoli said. ''God smiled on us Sunday,
and let's hope he's in a good mood the rest of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivoli said a few small bridges on Route 57 near the
Musconetcong River were closed Tuesday as a precaution as workers
continue to monitor the river's level.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't say when it'll surge,'' he said. ''It's a
wait-and-see game.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the state is investigating claims that 14 inches of
rain fell Saturday in Sparta when a storm system stalled over the
hilly region. A better estimate is 8 inches to 10 inches, said
David Robinson, state climatologist at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   NJ Transit said bus and rail service out of Hackettstown is
scheduled to resume Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The dam on Seneca Lake in Sparta burst over the weekend,
emptying it and leaving a 25-acre patch of mud.
</P>
<P>
   The floods also destroyed the Tomahawk water park in Sparta
where earthen dams burst and emptied Seneca and Tomahawk lakes,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Other dams that have failed include those at Hawthorne Lake in
Sparta, Shawnee Lake in Jefferson, and Lake Tomahawk in Byram,
state officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-15-00 2227 </TRAILER>
